<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Romania to Expand Danube Delta Woodland </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BUCHAREST, April 6 (Xinhua) -- Romania's River Danube Delta
research institute issued a project to replenish forests in the
Danube Delta, due to run until the year 2015, after winning
financial support from the World Bank.
</P>
<P>
Approximately 300 hectares of land by the Chilia branch and 400
hectares by the Sf. Gheorghe branch, two of the Danube's three
arms that make a vast wetland before they empty into the Black
Sea, will be afforested under the provisions of the program.
</P>
<P>
The first bout of this enterprise kicked off in 1998. Wood
plantation works are aimed to breathe fresh life into the
environment of the Delta region, by making up for vast swathes of
woodland lost to the irrigation, diking, draining and landscaping
fever over the course of the past decades, when heed for sensible
conservation practices was utterly missing.
</P>
<P>
The Natural Reservation of the Danube Delta encompasses 580,000
hectares, the equivalent of 2.5 percent of Romania's landmass, and
is the third in importance after the Amazon Delta and the Nile
Delta.
</P>
<P>
The Danube Delta area is home to hundreds of bird species and
it is the only sanctuary in the world which 176 of these species
can tolerate for nesting.
</P>
<P>
Rare birds like the red-collar duck, accounting for 90 percent
of the world population, the white egret, 71 percent, and the
Lilliputian cormorant, 61 percent, have found their home in the
Danube Delta area.
</P>
<P>
The waters of the Danube Delta accomodate numberless fishes, of
which some of industrial value, like carp, catfish, pike, and
migratory sturgeons.
</P>
<P>
In December 1990, the Natural Reservation of the River Danube
Delta was included by UNESCO into the world cultural heritage. The
non-refundable financial assistance project was signed with the
World Bank on August 24, 1994, and it is worth 4.5 million U.S.
dollars. It centers on the protection and development of the
ecosystem in this area.
</P>
<P>
The project also provides for the unfolding of a monitoring
program, due to take stock of the species living in the Danube
Delta, oversee the ecosystem and the hydrographic basin. 
</P>
</TEXT>
