<HEADLINE> Security Council Extends UN Mission on Iraq-Kuwait Border </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, April 6 (Xinhua) -- The United Nations Security
Council on Tuesday agreed to extend U.N. observer mission on the
Iraq-Kuwait boder for another six months.
</P>
<P>
The move came after the Security Council reviewed the latest
report by U.N. Secretary-General Kofi Annan on the mission.
</P>
<P>
Speaking to the press, Council President Alain Dejammet of
France said the Council agreed to the routine extension without
any debate.
</P>
<P>
Annan said in his report that the U.S. and British airstrikes
against Iraq did not significantly affect the U.N. observer
mission during the period from September 24, 1998 to March 23,
1999.
</P>
<P>
The 1,311-strong U.N. mission has been monitoring the
demilitarized zone along the border since the Gulf War.  
</P>
</TEXT>
