<HEADLINE> WFP Appeals for Food Aid to Refugees in Tanzania </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, April 5 (Xinhua) -- The United Nations World
Food Program (WFP) Tuesday called on donors to offer food aid to
beef up food stock for the refugees sheltered in western Tanzania.
</P>
<P>
The program's country director Irene Lacy said here that during
the past two months, a shortage of funds has forced the United
Nations agency to use buffer stock in most camps to feed refugees.
</P>
<P>
There are some 350,000 refugees from the Democratic Republic of
Congo, Rwanda and Burundi in the camps in the Kigoma and Kagera
regions in northwestern Tanzania, which requires a total of 7,000
tons of food per month.
</P>
<P>
At the moment, said Lacy, WFP has a food stock for only six
weeks and additional quantities will be urgently needed to
maintain ration levels for recipients.
</P>
<P>
"We hope to receive announcements of additional pledges during
the coming weeks thus easing the pressure which currently exists,"
she said.
</P>
<P>
Lacy explained that refugees in Tanzania were currently being
provided with a daily ration of maize or maize meal, pulses, oil,
a blended food and salt.
</P>
<P>
The United States Agency for International Development has so
far promised 4,500 tons of food worth 1.6 million U.S. dollars and
the first wagon containing food from Uganda arrived in Tanzania
Monday, she said.
</P>
<P>
Another shipment of food from South Africa is expected within
the next four to five weeks. However, the U.N. official noted
that food delivery during existing rainy seasons is very tough.
</P>
<P>
"Competing demands around the world make it very difficult for
donors to prioritize assistance," she said, adding that Tanzania
itself is also suffering an acute shortage of food for its
population. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
