<HEADLINE> Feature: NATO Bombing Shatters Milica's Dream </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ALEKSINAC, Yugoslavia, April 6 (Xinhua) -- For 13-year-old
Milica, playing piano is part of daily life, but a NATO bomb on
Monday disrupted her tranquil life and shattered her music dream.
</P>
<P>
Her piano now lies on the second floor of her roofless
two-story house on the Vuk Karadic street, one of the busiest
residential quarters in this mining town some 200 kilometers south
of Belgrade.
</P>
<P>
Milica and her 19-year-old sister Jelena and 8-year-old Milan
were scavenging the rubbles for whatever was still usable. They
dug out books, Milica's award certificates and a Zenith camera.
</P>
<P>
When the bomb exploded near their house, Milica, Jelena and
Milan were staying with their parents in a village house nearby.
Their 70-year-old grandfather, Branko, was thrown out of his bed
in the second floor and landed on the ground. Their grandmother,
68, was crushed in the bathroom on the first floor.
</P>
<P>
The two old couple were seriously wounded and are now in an
intensive care unit in a hospital in neighboring Nis, Jelena said,
taking snapshots of what was remaining of her house.
</P>
<P>
The owners of the neighboring building, which was almost
totally demolished, 70-year-old Vlastimir, his wife Vukica and
their daughter Snezen, perished in the blast. Vlastimir's
15-year-old granddaughter Diane and 10-year-old Marko were
severely wounded.
</P>
<P>
The destruction was much worse in a 10,000 square meter
residential area several hundred meters away on the Dusana Trevnca
street, where a second NATO bomb landed.
</P>
<P>
About 11 apartments were reduced to rubbles. A patch of
blood-soaked ground could be seen amid such articles as a
children's tricycle, two umbrellas and one black shoe.
</P>
<P>
The owner of one flattened house picked up one vase and two
plastic glasses from the ruins, too distraught to tell her name
and what happened to her family.
</P>
<P>
Nearby, water could be heard leaking from that damaged pipes,
as if mourning the 12 innocent civilian victims of NATO bombing.
More than 30 were gravely wounded in the city of 30,000 people.
</P>
<P>
The strong explosion shattered the tiles and glasses of many
houses nearby. When a group of foreign reporters arrived on
Tuesday afternoon, residents were still cleaning the streets,
which were strewn with broken glasses, tiles, and window and door
frames.
</P>
<P>
A old man with a bandaged skull and stains of blood on his
shoulder could be seen staggering along.
</P>
<P>
"There was air-raid sirens before the bombing, but we had no
shelter to go," said 40- year-old fashion designer Zora Milykovic,
who was three months pregnant.
</P>
<P>
Stana Stojavic, a 62-year-old woman who witnessed the massacres
of Nazis soldiers during the Second World War, could not believe
what had happened Monday night.
</P>
<P>
"We didn't invade any country. Here are all old people,
children. They are all civilians. No military targets. Why did
NATO bomb us?
</P>
<P>
"Is killing innocent civilians democracy?" she asked. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
