<HEADLINE> Kenya Parliament Resumes After Recess </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, April 6 (Xinhua) -- The Kenyan National Assembly
resumed Tuesday after a four-month recess since Christmas with a
speech made by Kenyan President Daniel arap Moi.
</P>
<P>
"Unemployment, hunger, malnutrition and the burden of
cost-sharing in schools and hospitals are some of the problems
that call for our urgent attention," said Moi.
</P>
<P>
Poor roads, inadequate supply of water, energy and
communication facilities also continue to hamper the efforts to
raise economic growth rates, the president added.
</P>
<P>
Moi also noted that the structural adjustment policies required
by the International Monetary Fund resulted in painful
consequences in a short term, increasing unemployment and
worsening the poverty situation.
</P>
<P>
With regard to poverty eradication, Moi said "a lasting
solution to the problem of poverty can only be achieved through
the realization of higher economic growth rate".
</P>
<P>
On anti-corruption, the president said the government had
established the Kenyan Anti-Corruption Authority to deal with
cases of corruption and urged the members of parliament to
support the anti-graft body.
</P>
<P>
Regarding security, Moi said the government had taken the
necessary actions to increase budgetary resources to strengthen
the security of the borders under a circumstance where insecurity
in the neighboring countries increase.
</P>
<P>
Moi also appealed to all Kenyans to cooperate and unite to
address the problems the country faces, such as the
constitutional review stalemate.
</P>
<P>
Moi's speech has drew mixed reactions from members of
parliament. Vice- President George Saitoti and Attorney General
S.A. Wako were confident that Moi's speech will guide the
government toward a success.
</P>
<P>
However, parliament members from opposition parties said they
could not see any concrete measures to solve the problems Kenya
faces through the speech.
</P>
<P>
This session of parliament is the last one in this millenium.
During the session, the government will table a number of bills
for discussion by the parliament. These will include the Traffic
Bill and the Medical Laboratory Technicians and Technologists
Bill, the Industrial Property Bill, the Tea Bill and the Kenya
Roads Board Bill.
</P>
<P>
Kenyan National Assembly is one-house parliament with 224
members. President Moi's ruling party Kenyan African National
Union (KANU) has 114 seats in current session. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
