<HEADLINE> UK Scientists Develop Nutritive "Designer Egg" </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, April 6 (Xinhua) -- Scientists in Scotland have
developed a new type of chicken egg that can help cut the risk of
a variety of diseases.
</P>
<P>
The so-called "designer egg", announced at the on-going
Edinburgh Science Festival, has raised levels of four important
chemicals including vitamin E, docosahexaenic fatty acid (DHA),
lutein and selenium.
</P>
<P>
Since early study has linked increased level of these chemicals
with a decreased risk of different diseases, the scientists, from
the Scottish Agricultural College, believed that the new "designer
egg" may help reduce the risk of heart disease and some cancers.
</P>
<P>
The researchers stressed that the nutritive quality of the
"designer egg" has been improved by enhancing the diet of laying
hens, a process which does not involve genetic modification.
</P>
<P>
The college is now seeking a commercial partner to bring the
egg to market, the researchers said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
