<HEADLINE> Closed Palestinian Offices to Appeal Israeli Order </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, April 6 (Xinhua) -- The Palestinian offices in East
Jerusalem shut down by Israel will appeal the closure orders to
Israel's High Court of Justice, the Voice of Palestine reported
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Jawad Bulus, the lawyer appointed by the three Palestinian
offices, said the closure orders issued by Israeli government were
"political, not legal," the radio said.
</P>
<P>
Israeli police Sunday served closure orders on the Palestinian
News Agency, the Palestinian Prisoners Society and the Christian
Services Office, in East Jerusalem, claiming they have "close
cooperations" with the Palestinian National Authority (PNA).
</P>
<P>
Israeli authorities forbid PNA organs and offices to operate in
East Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
The closure decision was made on March 29 at a meeting attended
by Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu, Foreign Minister Ariel
Sharon, Defense Minister Moshe Arens and Public Security Minister
Avigdor Kahalani.
</P>
<P>
The PNA sharply criticized the decision last Thursday, terming
it "aggressive measures against Palestinian national institutions
in East Jerusalem" and "a challenge to international legitimacy."
</P>
<P>
Such decision was taken apparently to contain the Palestinian
political and diplomatic activities in the traditionally Arab East
Jerusalem, which Israel took in 1967 Mideast War.
</P>
<P>
Israel regards Jerusalem as its sovereign capital, a claim
rejected by the Palestinians, who said the holy city, especially
East Jerusalem, is an occupied territory.
</P>
<P>
The Palestinians want East Jerusalem to become the capital of
their future independent state. 
</P>
</TEXT>
