<HEADLINE> Europe's Map Should Not Be Changed: Talbott </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BUCHAREST, April 6 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. Deputy Secretary of
State Strobe Talbott Tuesday stressed here that it was imperative
that the Europe's map and that of the Balkan region as well,
should not be changed.
</P>
<P>
The American official made the remark to the press after his
meeting with Romanian Foreign Minister Andrei Plesu. Talbott
completed on the same day the last leg of a tour in countries
neighbouring Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
NATO's actions do not aim to change Europe's or the region's
map, but to find a satisfactory and acceptable solution to the
conflict in Kosovo, Talbott stressed.
</P>
<P>
Talbott hailed Romania's decision to get involved in seeking
for a solution to the issues in the area, adding that Romania
stands for a sure security exporter. He also expressed admiration
and gratitude for Romania's having assumed the difficult task of
receiving refugees from Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
He told the press that the American Government intended to
considerably increase the financial aid for Romania, announcing
that the bilateral assistance program was supplemented with six
million U.S. dollars, taking the total amount to 46.6 million U.S.
dollars.
</P>
<P>
Talbott believed that Romania was acting fairly, winning United
States' friendship. "The Romanian-U.S. strategic partnership has
gradually switched from an abstract concept to a specific re|ity,"
he said, promising that the NATO summit in Washington would
forcefully encourage the idea that Romania must become a partner
of the military bloc. 
</P>
</TEXT>
