<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ugandan Ministers May Face Censure After </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, April 6 (Xinhua) -- Ugandan ministers who have been
removed from their posts or moved to other positions for their
involvement in various scandals may still face censure by the
parliament, an official told Xinhua Tuesday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
Kagole Kivumbi, public relations officer with the parliament,
said:"The parliament is still studying and debating the report by
the select committee and those ministers implicated in the valley
dam scandal may still be censured."
</P>
<P>
"In the latest cabinet reshuffle, some ministers were just
moved to other positions. The parliament is considering whether
what the president has done is enough or not," the spokesman
added.
</P>
<P>
In the surprise cabinet reshuffle Monday, Vice President
Specioza Kazibwe was removed from the post of Minister of
Agriculture, Animal Industry and Fisheries which she had been
holding since 1995.
</P>
<P>
Of the two state ministers working under her, one is now in
charge of environment while the other remained state minister in
the ministry.
</P>
<P>
Three weeks ago, the report by the select committee on
agriculture recommended that the three ministers be removed for
failing to supervise the valley dam project which caused a
colossal loss of 3.4 billion shillings (3.4 million U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
Francis Babu, former state minister for primary education, was
discontinued from his Master Degree studies by the renowned
Makerere University recently for being short of the minimum
academic requirements. This scandal is also likely to make him
being censured by the legislature.
</P>
<P>
This time he was transferred to take care of energy and
minerals instead of being dropped out by the president.
</P>
<P>
If the parliament considers President Yoweri Museveni has not
done enough to clean the cabinet, members of parliament can
continue to press for censure against the above ministers.
</P>
</TEXT>
