<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-06 18:42 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> AL Welcomes Suspension of U.N. Sanctions on Libya </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, April 6 (Xinhua) -- The Arab League Secretary General
Esmat Abdel-Meguid on Tuesday expressed welcome to the suspension
of U.N. sanctions on Libya.
</P>
<P>
Abdel-Meguid said in a statement that Libya's handover of the
two suspects in the bombing a Pan Am jetliner for trial in the
Netherlands marks a final step towards ending a quandary.
</P>
<P>
Libya surrendered the two suspects on Monday to U.N.
representatives, who escorted them to a former U.S. military base
near the Hague, where they will be tried under Scottish law.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. Security Council announced Monday that the sanctions
imposed on Libya in 1992 was "automatically suspended" after U.N
Secretary General Kofi Annan informed it that the suspects had
arrived in the Netherlands.
</P>
<P>
The two Libyans were accused of blowing up the Pan Am flight
103 over Lockerbie, Scotland in 1988, killing 270 people. The
U.S. and Britain pressed the U.N. Security Council to impose the
sanctions, including ban on flights to and from Libya.
</P>
<P>
Abdel-Meguid reiterated the league's support for Libya's stand
on getting guarantees for a fair trial of the two suspects.
</P>
<P>
Washington and London had demanded that the two Libyans be
tried either in the U.S. or Britain. But fearing that its citizens
would not get a fair trial, Libya refused the demand, insisting
that the two be tried in a third, neutral country.
</P>
<P>
The two Western allies later compromised to agree that the two
Libyans be tried in the Netherlands before a Scottish court. If
convicted, they will be imprisoned in Scotland under U.N.
supervision. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
