<HEADLINE> Tanzanians Urged to Care Elders </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, April 6 (Xinhua) -- Tanzanian Health Minister
Aaron Chiduo Tuesday urged the society to give more care to the
elders as the number of aged people in the country is increasing
fast.
</P>
<P>
"The society must pay special attention to a positive life
habit and give consideration to recommended nutritious food,
environmental sanitation and body cleanness," Chiduo told a press
conference here in the capital, adding that a healthy life style
is the corner-stone of longevity.
</P>
<P>
The theme of this year's World Health Day which falls on April
7 is " physical strength in the elderly brings difference in
living and makes you appreciate your elderly state," he said.
</P>
<P>
The theme goes together with the International Year for the
Aged which was inaugurated on October 1 last year, he noted.
</P>
<P>
It has been estimated that there will be a total of 2.4 million
aged people in Tanzania in the year 2000, according to the 1988
national census.
</P>
<P>
The minister urged people to abandon bad customs in treating
the elders, for example, the rampant witch hunting practices in
several regions in which hundreds of innocent elderly people were
killed.
</P>
<P>
People's life expectancy has increased this century and as a
result the number of aged people has also increased in the world,
he said.
</P>
<P>
Statistics from the World Health Organization show that 580
million aged people are in their sixties and the number is
expected to increase by 75 percent to one billion in 20 years.
</P>
</TEXT>
