<HEADLINE> Germany to Receive First Kosovo Refugees Wednesday </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN April 6 (Xinhua)--Germany is expected to receive first 600
Kosovo refugees Wednesday afternoon in the southern city of
Nuremberg, Bavaria's Ministry for Social Affairs announced Tuesday
in Munich.
</P>
<P>
On Thursday there will be a total 10,000 refugees arriving in
Germany, Defense Minister Rudolf Scharping said in Bonn, adding
that the aged, the patients, and the help-needing children will be
given the priority of being flown from the crisis region by planes
of German forces.
</P>
<P>
About 2,240 of the ten thousand refugees will be at first sent
to the receive centers in the sate of North Rhine-Westphalia,
1,400 in Bavaria, 1,220 in Bade-Wurttemburg, with the remaining
sent to other German states.
</P>
<P>
Pro Asyl, an organization aiming at helping the Kosovo
refugees, has demanded Bonn admit more refugees than it has
promised, saying that Germany can and should receive at least
120,000 refugees, twice more than the German cabinet has decided
to receive.
</P>
<P>
Aiding the refugees in the spot is more emergent than recieving
them in Germany, Minister for Inen Affairs Otto Schilly argued
Tuesday in Bonn.
</P>
<P>
The German forces will strengthen its air transportation of aid
for refugees in Albania and Macedonia, Scharping said, quoting
that by now there are at least six flights per day from Germany to
the region.
</P>
<P>
A total 150 tons of food, medicine, sleeping bags and camps
were carried for the refugees on this Tuesday by German planes,
and German forces has planned to deploy an Airbus plane for aid
transportation, Scharping said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
