<HEADLINE> U.S. Rejects Ceasefire Offer by Belgrade </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, April 6 (Xinhua) -- The United States on Tuesday
rejected a unilateral ceasefire offer by Yugoslavia in Kosovo and
President Bill Clinton reiterated the terms to end NATO's
airstrikes.
</P>
<P>
"We've made very clear that any hollow, half measures will not
stop the bombing," said David Leavy, a White House spokesman.
</P>
<P>
"NATO operations will continue until these conditions are met,"
said Leavy.
</P>
<P>
In an interview with the Voice of America (VOA), Defense
Secretary William Cohen said the Yugoslav cease-fire offer is "not
only completely unacceptable but it's absurd."
</P>
<P>
Cohen also said he was flying to NATO headquarters in Belgium
Tuesday to consult with alliance military and political leaders.
</P>
<P>
Earlier on Tuesday, Yugoslav Foreign Minister Vuk Draskovic
announced Belgrade had called an imminent unilateral ceasefire.
</P>
<P>
The United States insists Belgrade meet all of demands by the
North Atlantic Treaty Organization (NATO), including withdrawal of
Serb forces from Kosovo and allowing ethnic Albanian refugees to
return.
</P>
<P>
During a White House ceremony, Clinton said that NATO's
airstrikes will end if Belgrade withdraws its forces from Kosovo,
accepts terms of a peace accord and allows refugees to return.
</P>
<P>
"The United States would never choose force as anything other
than a last option," Clinton said when speaking of the crisis in
Kosovo briefly.
</P>
<P>
"Mr. (Slobodan) Milosevic could end it now by withdrawing his
military.... and paramilitary forces,... by accepting the
deployment of an international security force to protect not only
the Kosovar Albanians... but also the Serbian minority... and by
making it possible for all the refugees to return," Clinton added.
</P>
</TEXT>
