<HEADLINE> Palestinian, Lebanese Officials Hold Talks on </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, April 6 (Xinhua) -- Lebanese Minister of Post,
Telephone and Telegram Issam Naaman and visiting senior
Palestinian official in charge of refugees affairs Abdel Rahman
held talks over Palestinian refugees in Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
During the meeting, the two officials reached an agreement to
set up a joint committee to handle the livelihood of Palestinian
refugees in Lebanon in line with international human rights
standards, the official National News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
Some 350,000 Palestinians are now living in 12 refugee camps
across Lebanon under the financial support by the United Nations
Relief and Works Agency.
</P>
<P>
They were forced to flee their homes since Israel declared an
independent state on May 14, 1948.
</P>
<P>
The Lebanese government, which has been kept alert about the
permanent settlement of these Palestinians in Lebanon, imposed
strict limits on their jobs in the country.
</P>
<P>
Rahman told a news conference after the talks that Palestine
categorically opposes the permanent settlement as the
U.N. Resolution 194 grants Palestinians the right to return home
and claim compensations.
</P>
<P>
He expressed thanks for the efforts made by the new Lebanese
regime of President Emile Lahoud and Prime Minister Salim Hoss to
deal with the Palestinian affairs.
</P>
<P>
As soon as Lahoud came to power last November and set up the
new government led by Hoss in January, Lebanese security
authorities eased travel restrictions on Palestinian refugees.
</P>
<P>
They were granted easier entry and departure from and to
Lebanon. 
</P>
</TEXT>
