<HEADLINE> Security Council Supports UN Mission in Guinea-Bissau </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, April 6 (Xinhua) -- The United Nations Security
Council on Tuesday voiced its support for the establishment of a
Post-conflict Peace Building Support Office in Guinea-Bissau
(UNOGBIS).
</P>
<P>
The move came after the Security Council reviewed the report by
the U.N. Secretary-General Kofi Annan on the latest situation in
the country.
</P>
<P>
In its resolution unanimously adopted, the Council said
UNOGBIS, which would be led by a representative of the
Secretary-General, aimed to provide the political framework and
leadership for harmonizing and integrating the activities of the
United Nations system in Guinea-Bissau during the transitional
period leading up to general election and to facilitate the
implementation of the Abuja Agreement.
</P>
<P>
The Council reiterated that the primary responsibility for
achieving lasting peace in the country rested with the parties
concerned and strongly called upon them to implement fully all the
provisions of the Abuja Agreement and subsequent undertakings.
</P>
<P>
The Council urged the parties concerned promptly to agree on a
date for the holding of elections as soon as possible which were
all-inclusive, free and fair, and invite the United Nations and
others to consider providing any needed electoral assistance.
</P>
<P>
The Council demanded that all concerned respect strictly the
relevant provisions of international law, including international
humanitarian law and human rights law, to ensure safe and
unimpeded access by humanitarian organizations to those in need
and to ensure the protection and freedom of movement of United
Nations and international humanitarian personnel.
</P>
<P>
The Council requested the U.N. chief to keep it regularly
informed and to submit a report to it by June 30, 1999 and every
90 days thereafter on development in the country, the activities
of UNOGBIS and the implementation of the Abuja Agreement. 
</P>
</TEXT>
