<HEADLINE> Iraq Signed 117 Deals on Oil Spare Parts: Official </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD, April 6 (Xinhua) -- Iraq has signed 117 contracts
valued at 120 million U.S. dollars in the current fifth phase of
the oil-for-food program to purchase oil spare parts, an Iraqi Oil
Ministry official said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Director General of the Planning and Studies Department at the
Oil Ministry Falih Hassan Marhoon told the Iraqi News Agency that
39 contracts worth 24 million dollars had been submitted to the
U.N. Sanctions Committee for ratification.
</P>
<P>
Only after the ratification by the U.N. Sanctions Committee can
the contracts be implemented.
</P>
<P>
Marhoon said more contracts will be signed in the current phase
with the allocated amount, which runs from last November to June.
</P>
<P>
The U.N., which slapped sanctions on Iraq following its
invasion of Kuwait in 1990, in an oil-for-food deal allows Iraq to
export limited amount of oil every six months since November 1996
to buy food, medicine and other humanitarian goods.
</P>
<P>
Iraq has been allowed in the fourth and fifth phases to import
300 million dollars worth of oil spare parts to increase its oil
production and export capacity.
</P>
<P>
Marhoon said that most of the contracts signed in the current
phase had been concluded in the last six-month period, which
mainly include chemical, service and operational items badly
needed in Iraq's dilapidated oil industry.
</P>
<P>
But only 25 of the 750 contracts concluded in the fourth phase
have been implemented and spare parts worth no more than 15
million dollars have arrived in Iraq so far, said Marhoon.
</P>
<P>
Marhoon held the U.S. and Britain responsible for the delay of
ratifying the contracts Iraq concluded with world companies.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
