<DOCNO> XIE19990407.0032 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Commentary: Hegemonism Under Pretext of Humanitarianism </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 6 (Xinhua) -- The escalating military attacks
waged by the U.S.-led NATO against Yugoslavia have proven to be
nothing but hegemonism practiced under the pretext of
humanitarianism.
</P>
<P>
The targets of airstrikes have been expanded to factories,
schools, roads, airports and other civilian facilities over recent
days.
</P>
<P>
The air raids inflicted a disastrous loss of life and property
on the Yugoslav people, arousing strong indignation and
condemnation of all peace-loving people who uphold justice,
including those of NATO members.
</P>
<P>
However, NATO has repeatedly argued that the airstrikes aimed "
to prevent a humanitarian disaster" and "safeguard human rights."
</P>
<P>
Is NATO really "preventing a humanitarian disaster" or creating
a humanitarian disaster? Is it "safeguarding human rights" or
violating human rights? Facts speak louder:
</P>
<P>
According to statistics made by Yugoslavia, NATO flew more than
430 sorties, launched about 400 cruise missiles and employed
various advanced weapons including stealth bombers in the first
week alone since the air raids started. The power of the bombs
dropped on the land of Yugoslavia is double that of the atomic
bombs dropped by the United States in Hiroshima.
</P>
<P>
A prominent American scholar wrote in USA Today on March 26
that the attacks against Yugoslavia are a brazen aggression,
because American troops are attacking a country that has not
attacked the U.S., nor the U.S. allies nor its neighboring
countries.
</P>
<P>
In an article in Romania's Adevarul on April 1, the author
wrote that the airstrikes against Yugoslavia by the U.S.-led NATO
are not for "human rights" and "peace" which they have flaunted so
much. Actually, the sole purpose of the strikes is nothing but to
unleash a war.
</P>
<P>
Since the death of countless civilians in Europe means nothing
serious to the U.S., NATO's pretexts for the attacks against
Yugoslavia are ridiculous and unreasonable, the author wrote.
</P>
<P>
After bombing military targets in Yugoslavia, NATO has switched
its targets to civilian facilities. Up to now, NATO has bombed
important bridges, railway lines, factories, schools and
government buildings in Yugoslavia. Even hospitals and heating
systems in Belgrade and scenic spots in Kosovo were not spared by
NATO air forces.
</P>
<P>
Large numbers of houses were burnt and thousands of civilians
killed. Millions of people have to stay in air-raid shelters
without access to water, electricity and food.
</P>
<P>
NATO's airstrikes have inflicted an immediate loss of billions
of U.S. dollars to Yugoslavia. And indirect impacts, such
potential damage to ecological environment and the trauma of war,
are beyond calculation.
</P>
<P>
NATO claimed that its airstrikes on Yugoslavia aimed to prevent
an escalation of bloodshed and a mass exodus of refugees in Kosovo
and further to avert a "humanitarian disaster" in the heart of
Europe.
</P>
<P>
However, it was during NATO's bombardments that Serbian and
ethnic Albanian refugees in Kosovo were forced to leave their
homeland and pour into neighboring countries to flee the flames of
war.
</P>
<P>
The refugee wave is bringing pressure upon some countries such
as Albania and Macedonia, and is posing a serious threat to
security and stability of the whole Balkan region.
</P>
<P>
Obviously, it is NATO itself that created the "humanitarian
disaster" in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
Even ethnic Albanian leader Ibrahim Rugova, who has called for
NATO intervention in Kosovo, is now demanding NATO halt its
bombing of Yugoslavia, urging the Western military alliance to "
stop killings."
</P>
<P>
This indeed constitutes a great irony for NATO countries which
have all along been trumpeting about human rights.
</P>
<P>
Disguising themselves as the "champion of human rights," the
United States and other Western countries frequently attacked
other countries for alleged "human rights problems" or "inhumane
practices." However, the NATO military operations have threatened
the lives of 12 million Yugoslav people at the moment. Can this
be called a "humanitarian act"? Is this an act of defending human
rights?
</P>
<P>
According to German news reports, some veteran politicians from
Germany's former Green Party denounced the airstrikes of the U.S.-
led NATO as a "violation of human rights."
</P>
<P>
The media in some developing countries pointed out that it is
the U.S.-led NATO that is the number one violator of human rights
in the world.
</P>
<P>
Problems like the Kosovo crisis, which are part of internal
affairs of countries, also exist in some member countries of NATO.
But why does NATO turn a complete blind eye and deaf ear to those
facts and use its force to bully a small country like Yugoslavia?
The reason is that the U.S. and other Western countries have
always pursued double standards on human rights issues. Because
the Kosovo issue concerns U.S. strategic interests in Europe, the
U.S.-led NATO unleashed massive strikes against Yugoslavia under
the pretext of "human rights violations."
</P>
<P>
An article carried by the Finish "Capital Daily" on March 31
said the conflicts in Kosovo could not become an excuse for the U.
S. to bomb Yugoslavia. The move by the U.S. and its NATO allies
to circumvent the United Nations to launch attacks on a sovereign
country can only be viewed as an act of hegemonism. They have set
an abominable precedent in the history of international relations
to defy the U.N. Charter and universally accepted norms of
international law and bypass the U.N. Security Council to openly
use force and flagrantly interfere in the internal affairs of a
sovereign country.
</P>
<P>
At the turning of the century, peace and development are the
common aspirations of all peoples in the world. Power politics
and hegemonism have lost their markets. The U.S.-led NATO should
immediately stop its airstrikes against Yugoslavia and bring the
Kosovo issue back to the track of political resolution. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
