<HEADLINE> Russia Urges Ministerial Meeting of G8 on Kosovo </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, April 6 (Xinhua) -- Russia has called for an urgent
meeting of the foreign ministers of the so-called Group of Eight
to discuss the Yugoslavia crisis, said Russian Foreign Minister
Igor Ivanov Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The complicated situation in Yugoslavia allows no time for low-
level meetings. There are more bombings, more tragedies and more
deaths in Yugoslavia every day, said Ivanov after a cabinet
meeting on the Yugoslavia issue.
</P>
<P>
G8 groups Russia, Britain, France, Germany, Italy, the United
States, Canada and Japan. The countries except Canada and Japan
comprise the Contact Group on Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
Ivanov said that Russia would come up with fresh peace
proposals.
</P>
<P>
The minister criticized Western media for defending NATO for
creating a humanitarian disaster in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
The exodus of more than 100,000 refugees from Kosovo occurred
after NATO launched air strikes on Yugoslavia on March 24, he said.
</P>
<P>
When asked if it's possible for Russia to get into a military
confrontation with the West, particularly NATO, Ivanov stressed
that it's up to President Boris Yeltsin to decide a political or
military position.
</P>
<P>
Yeltsin has said that Russia would not get militarily involved
in the Yugoslavia crisis. 
</P>
