<BODY>
<HEADLINE> White Collar Crime in Germany Surging During 1990s </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, April 6 (Xinhua)--The number of white collar crimes in
German companies has been rising steeply during the 1990s, a
financial publication reported on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
More than half of all German firms are now affected by white
collar misdeeds such as embezzlement, fraud and misappropriation,
the magazine "Die Bank" published by the Cologne-based Federation
of German Banks said.
</P>
<P>
In 1991 there were 435,000 cases of white collar crime
registered by the police, with a total damage of about 4 billion
marks (2.2 billion U.S. dollars). The numbers had reached 780,000
and 12.6 billion respectively in year 1997.
</P>
<P>
The white collar crimes probably increased further in the last
year, the magazine indicated.
</P>
<P>
The magazine quoted a study of Germany's 1,000 largest firms in
year 1997 by an auditing company that 61 per cent of them reported
being victims of white collar crimes during the proceeding 5
years.
</P>
<P>
More than two-thirds of the companies said that internal
misdeeds had aroused serious problems, while 84 per cent planned
to strengthen internal controls.
</P>
<P>
The data showed that 45 per cent of the crimes were committed
by company employees, 38 per cent were by persons outside a
company, the remaining were by a combination of the two groups.
</P>
<P>
Many companies believed there were two factors behind the rise
of white collar crimes. One is the increasing complexity of
business transaction procedure, and another is more complicated
corporate structure, which is often the result of mergers or
takeovers. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
