<HEADLINE> Zimbabwe's Secondary Schools To Teach Human Rights </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, April 6 (Xinhua) -- Zimbabwe's Education, Sport and
Culture Minister Gabriel Machinga said Tuesday that about 18
secondary schools in the country will teach human rights in the
next semester.
</P>
<P>
The schools would teach the subject on a pilot project before
it is implemented in all schools by the year 2001.
</P>
<P>
"We have two options, either to teach the subject separately or
 integrate it in related subjects like history," he said.
</P>
<P>
The minister made the remarks when opening a four-day
Sub-Regional Trainers' Workshop on Human Rights and Democracy
Education which started in Harare Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The workshop is being attended by education officers and heads
of curriculum development units from Namibia, Mozambique and
Zimbabwe and representatives of some non-governmental
organizations.
</P>
<P>
Sub-Regional Advisor of the United Nations Educational,
Scientific and Cultural Organization (UNESCO), Melania Rukanda
said that the workshop would come up with plans for the training
of teachers in pilot projects in the participating countries.
</P>
<P>
"We believe that if young people are taught to respect others
and themselves, we will have peace in our region which is
essential for development," said Rukanda.
</P>
<P>
"Elements of human rights are there in the curricula of most
southern African countries but there is no deliberate policy to
teach human rights as a subject," he said.
</P>
<P>
The workshop follows two others which were held in Namibia last
November and in Mozambique in March this year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
