<HEADLINE> Kasoulides: Cyprus Concerned Over Developments in Kosovo </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ATHENS, April 6 (Xinhua) -- Visiting Cyprus Foreign Minister
Ioannis Kasoulides on Tuesday expressed Nicosia's concern over
developments in Kosovo, stressing that military operations did not
help resolve the crisis.
</P>
<P>
Speaking after talks with his Greek counterpart George
Papandreou, Kasoulides said that the Cypriot people were concerned
about Kosovo since they were witnesses to developments and
conflicts which bring destabilization and of course human
suffering.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus attached great importance to the territorial integrity
of states, international law and the role of the United Nations
Security Council, he said, adding that military operations by the
North Atlantic Treaty Organization (NATO) did not help settle the
Kosovo problem.
</P>
<P>
When asked about the possibility of developments in Kosovo
having adverse repercussions for the Cyprus problem, the minister
said that Cyprus was indeed concerned.
</P>
<P>
Part of this concern had to do with the role of the United
Nations Security Council and the inviolability of borders, he
noted.
</P>
<P>
Kasoulides did not rule out an awaited U.S. initiative on the
Cyprus problem being put off if the Kosovo crisis continued with
the same intensity.
</P>
<P>
He said that international moves were expected on the Cyprus
problem following national elections in Turkey, and within this
framework, he would request a meeting in the summer, under U.N.
auspices, between Cyprus President Glafcos Clerides and Turkish
Cypriot leader Rauf Denktash.
</P>
<P>
Kasoulides, who arrived here Tuesday, talked with Papandreou on
issues of Kosovo, developments in the Balkans, the Cyprus problem
and Nicosia's entry into the European Union (EU). 
</P>
</TEXT>
