<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Rwandan Genocide Suspect Still Held in Tanzania </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, April 6 (Xinhua) -- Tanzania said Tuesday that
Bernard Ntuyahaga, a Rwandan army officer accused of murdering 10
Belgian peace-keepers during the 1994 Rwanda genocide, is still in
detention waiting for legal judgement.
</P>
<P>
"Ntuyahaga is still in the hands of (the Tanzanian)
government," one official with the Ministry of Justice and
Constitutional Affairs, told reporters at his office in Dar es
Salaam.
</P>
<P>
The official, who declined to be named, said that the
government is following procedures to hand over Ntuyahaga's case
to the Resident Magistrate's Court since the man is an illegal
citizen in Tanzania.
</P>
<P>
The officer refused to say which country Tanzania prefers to
expel Ntuyahaga to, noting that the government will follow the
court ruling. He did not reveal when the case will be dealt with.
</P>
<P>
Both Rwanda and Belgium have demanded that the suspect be
extradited to them after the United Nations court in the northern
Tanzanian town of Arusha, the International Criminal Tribunal for
Rwanda (ICTR), dropped all charges against him and released him in
Dar es Salaam last month.
</P>
<P>
Ntuyahaga was previously accused of ordering the murder of
Rwanda's former prime minister and the 10 Belgian soldiers
deployed to protect her at the start of 1994 genocide in which
more than 500,000 people were killed.
</P>
<P>
Ntuyahaga, 47, entered Tanzania and surrendered himself to the
ICTR in July of 1998. The tribunal was established by the U.N.
Security Council in November of 1994 to bring the architects of
the Rwanda genocide to justice.
</P>
<P>
Tanzania's Minister of Justice and Constitutional Affairs,
Bakari Mwapachu, said last week that Tanzania might charge
Ntuyahaga with violating its immigration laws but had not decided
whether to extradite him or not. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
