<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cholera Rampant in Southern, Central Somalia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOGADISHU, April 6 (Xinhua) -- Rampant cholera has killed
hundreds of people in southern and central regions of Somalia
recently, local officials said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The district commissioner of Qoryoley town, Ali Hussein Aliyow
Ibrow said that more than 110 people have died of cholera in the
past few days alone in the town and its surrounding villages, some
70 kilometers south of capital Mogadishu.
</P>
<P>
The other neighboring regions of Middle Jubba and Bay are not
any better.
</P>
<P>
Reports from the town of Jilib indicate that 30 people have
died from the disease in the past two weeks while over 200 others
are now in critical condition.
</P>
<P>
Abdurahman Hajji Ahmed Waldirch, one traditional leader of the
town told reporters in Mogadishu Tuesday morning that the victims
are mainly the elderly people and children.
</P>
<P>
Likewise , the disease is affecting people in the central
region of Galgudud, hitting the districts of Adado and Galhareri.
</P>
<P>
Two people were reported to have died in Adado town and more
than 30 others are now in critical condition, while in Galhareri
district, three people have been killed and more than 40 others
are still in critical condition.
</P>
<P>
The health authorities said the disease spread so fast that it
 immediately got out of control since it broke out in late March.
</P>
<P>
The absence of chlorine for purifying drinking water and the
anti-dehydration solution and poor sanitation were attributed to
the fast spread of the disease.
</P>
<P>
The disease which is said to break out at the end of every year
has early this year claimed the lives of more than 300 people in
Gedo and Bay regions where a high influx of war- and
drought-displaced people had gathered. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990407.0046 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Food Prices Hike up in Lusaka </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, April 6 (Xinhua) -- Food prices increased by about 30
percent in the Zambian capital of Lusaka between January 1998 and
January 1999, according to a survey.
</P>
<P>
The monthly survey by the Economic and Social Development
Research project of the Jesuit Centre for Theological Reflection
shows that the monthly food basket for a family of six has
steadily been rising from 186, 950 kwacha (about 70 U.S. dollars)
in January of 1998 to 240,920 kwacha (about 100 dollars) in
January this year.
</P>
<P>
Alex Muyebe of the center said in a statement released here
Tuesday that the monthly cost of food for the family of six
reached 252,000 Kwacha last month.
</P>
<P>
The cost does not includes other payment for essential
commodities such as water, electricity, housing, education and
health, says the survey.
</P>
<P>
Muyebe said the center supports President Frederick Chiluba's
assurance that civil servants will not be getting less than
200,000 kwacha beginning next year.
</P>
<P>
He said the salaries of the civil servants should be increased
to 250, 000 kwacha to match with the hiking food prices.
</P>
<P>
He also suggested that the base rate for beginning pay (pay as
you earn) should be over 250,000 kwacha in order to ease the tax
burden on the poor.
</P>
<P>
Last month Chiluba promised to narrow wage gap between those
ordinary civil servants and those in management.
</P>
<P>
Chiluba said next year the government will look at how it can
motivate those in income who are paid peanuts.
</P>
<P>
In Zambia a hospital nurse's monthly salary stands at about
100,000 kwacha. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990407.0047 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-06 20:14 </DATE_TIME>
