<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Three Rwandan Genocide Suspects Arrested in </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, April 6 (Xinhua) -- Three former Rwandan
ministers suspected of involvement in the 1994 genocide in Rwanda
were arrested Tuesday in Cameroon, a United Nations court
statement said.
</P>
<P>
Jerome Blcamumpaka, former Minister of Foreign Affairs, Prosper
 Mugiraneza, former Minister Responsible for Civil Service and
Justin Mugenzi, former Minister of Commerce, were arrested in and
near Yaounde, capital of Cameroon.
</P>
<P>
The statement from the International Criminal Tribunal for
Rwanda (ICTR) based in Tanzania's northern town Arusha said their
transfer is expected as soon as the formalities are completed in
Cameroon.
</P>
<P>
"The (ICTR) prosecutor, Justice Louise Arbour, expressed her
gratitude to the government of Cameroon for its assistance and
cooperation in this matter,!1 the statement added.
</P>
<P>
"These arrests bring to 38 the number of persons detained under
the authority of the Tribunal.
</P>
<P>
Established on November 8, 1994 by the U.N. Security Council,
the ICTR has the mandate to try persons suspected to be
responsible for genocide and other serious violations of the
international humanitarian law committed in the territory of
Rwanda between January 1 and December 31, 1994.
</P>
<P>
It also has the mandate to try Rwandan citizens responsible for
such violations committed in the territory of neighboring states.
</P>
<P>
The ICTR has so far issued 28 indictments against 45
individuals and a total of 36 indicted individuals are in custody,
35 of them in the U.N. Detention Facilities in Arusha and one is
detained in Texas of the United States.
</P>
<P>
About half a million Rwandans were reportedly killed during the
1994 genocide when the majority Hutus oppressed the minority
Tutsis. 
</P>
</TEXT>
