<HEADLINE> U.N. Hails Sudanese Government Ceasefire Declaration </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, April 6 (Xinhua) -- U.N.
Under-Secretary-General for Humanitarian Affairs Sergio Vieira de
Mello, Tuesday welcomed Monday's announcement by Sudanese
President Omar Hassan Al-Bashir on his government decision to
declare a comprehensive ceasefire in all the states of southern
Sudan.
</P>
<P>
"As the Secretary-General Special Envoy for Humanitarian
Assistance for the Sudan, Ambassador Tom Vraalsen is about to
undertake a mission to the region. I hope that the (rebel)
Sudanese People's Liberation Movement will use this opportunity to
reach a comprehensive ceasefire throughout southern Sudan," de
Mello said.
</P>
<P>
A cessation of hostilities would allow the U.N.-led Operation
Lifeline Sudan (OLS) to maximize its efforts to address the
humanitarian needs of civilians affected by the ongoing civil war,
U.N. spokesman Fred Eckhard said.
</P>
<P>
"I call on the international community to contribute generously
to the 1999 U.N. Inter-Agency Consolidated Appeal to Sudan through
which relief organizations aim at assisting some 2.3 million," de
Mello said.
</P>
<P>
The government-sanctioned comprehensive ceasefire will be
effective on April 15, when the partial ceasefire expires.
</P>
<P>
The Sudanese Government and the rebel Sudan People's Liberation
Army have agreed to three-month ceasefire in Bahr el-Ghazal since
October last year. International aid agencies and foreign
governments have called upon both warring sides to stop fighting to
allow food and medicine to the famine-struck province.
</P>
<P>
More than 1.9 million people have died in fighting and famine
since 1983, when the predominantly African southerners, of
Christian and animist faiths, began to fight for autonomy from the
Muslim North. 
</P>
</TEXT>
