<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Security Council Meets on Libya </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, April 6 (Xinhua) -- The U.N. Security Council
Tuesday continued the discussion on whether or not to have a draft
resolution or some other form of response to reflect the latest
developments concerning Libya.
</P>
<P>
U.N. spokesman Fred Eckhard told a press conference that the
latest developments include the Libyan handover of two Lockerbie
suspects for a trial before a Scottish court in the Netherlands, a
U.N. spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
Such developments also include the suspension of the sanctions
against Libya, he said.
</P>
<P>
The chairman of the committee which monitors the sanctions
against Libya is expected to issue a note verbale to States and
organizations restating that the sanctions have been suspended,
Eckhard said.
</P>
<P>
The president of the U.N. Security Council, Alain Dejammet of
France, Monday announced the suspension of the sanctions imposed
on Libya after the two suspects accused of the December 1988
bombing of a Pan Am airliner over Lockerbie, Scotland, had arrived
in the Netherlands for a trial before the Scottish court.
</P>
<P>
In a statement to the reports, Dejammet said that the
conditions set forth in U.N. Security Council Resolution 1192 for
"the immediate suspension" of sanctions "have been fulfilled."
</P>
<P>
"These measures (sanctions) have been therefore effectively
suspended," the statement said.
</P>
<P>
"The Security Council stated its readiness to suspend these
measures with a view to lifting them" in accordance with relevant
U.N. resolutions, the statement said.
</P>
<P>
"The members of the Council express their deep satisfaction at
this development," the statement said. "They are grateful to the
Secretary-General as well as all the Governments that have
contributed to it."
</P>
<P>
With the letter from U.N. Secretary-General Kofi Annan to the
Council president reporting the arrival of the two suspects in the
Netherlands, the Security Council can automatically suspend the
sanctions imposed on Libya in 1992 and tightened in 1993.
</P>
<P>
After 90 days, the Security Council can vote to lift the
sanctions, which include bans on air travel, weapons sales and
types of oil equipment.
</P>
<P>
The bombing of the Pan Am airliner over Lockerbie killed a
total of 270 people.
</P>
<P>
London and Washington last August dropped their insistence that
the two suspects stand trial in either of the country, and Libya
accepted the offer to have the two tried before a Scottish court
in the Netherlands. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
