<HEADLINE> Egypt to Retrieve Antiques Smuggled to Jordan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, April 6 (Xinhua) -- Egypt will retrieve within a few
days 27 ancient Egyptian artifacts smuggled to Jordan, an official
in charge of Egypt's antiquities said on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The artifacts were seized last November at Jordan's Aqaba
seaport when smugglers were trying to take them into the kingdom
inside a lorry, Gaballah Ali Gaballah, Secretary General of
Egypt's Supreme Antiquities Council was quoted by Egypt's Middle
East News Agency as saying.
</P>
<P>
The precious items date back to the Ptolemaic times from about
367 to 246 BC, said the official without giving further details.
</P>
<P>
He said that to retrieve valuable antiques is part of the plan
of the Culture Ministry to restore Egypt's arts treasures stolen
and smuggled to foreign countries.
</P>
<P>
He cited the return in March of a number of rare artifacts
which had been smuggled to Britain.
</P>
<P>
Contacts between Egyptian and Jordanian officials are under way
on returning the smuggled items, Ali Gaballah said, adding that
the Jordanian side has pledged to send them back intact and punish
the culprits. 
</P>
</TEXT>
