<HEADLINE> Researchers Develop Faster, Heat-Tolerant Chip </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, April 6 (Xinhua) -- Professor James Kolodzey and
his colleagues at the University of Delaware in Newark, Delaware,
say they have successfully developed new semiconductor chips,
faster and more heat-tolerant than current silicon chips.
</P>
<P>
The new chips using an alloy of materials might replace silicon
in cellular phones and other electronic devices, the Wall Street
Journal reported Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Professor Kolodzey and his team found that a silicon carbide
alloy, consisting of silicon, carbon and germanium materials
similar to those in sand paper, could transmit electrical signals
at higher speeds than silicon and also withstand high
temperatures. The current computer chips cannot withstand high
temperatures.
</P>
<P>
The new chips based on the materials could be used in
high-temperature applications such as jet engines and car engines
as well as in ordinary cellular phones, said the professor.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990407.0055 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Leading Economic Indicators Rise Again in February </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, April 6 (Xinhua) -- The Conference Board said
Tuesday that the Index of Leading Economic Indicators climbed 0.2
percent, for a fifth straight month, in February.
</P>
<P>
The rise of the Index, a key economic barometer, signals that
the U.S. economy will continue to thrive in coming months.
</P>
<P>
Four of the 10 indicators that make up the index were positive,
including higher consumer expectations and lower first-time claims
for unemployment.
</P>
<P>
Economists said this is good news for investors and good for
the economy.
</P>
<P>
The Index is designed to forecast economic activity six to nine
months in advance.
</P>
<P>
The Conference Board, a private research group, also reported
that the coincident indicators, which measure current activity,
rose 0.3 percent and the lagging index, which measures the
economy's past performance, climbed 0.2 percent in February.
</P>
<P>
It said that the three index components show a healthy economy
and an economic expansion that will continue through at least late
1999.
</P>
<P>
The leading indicators are calculated from a base of 100, set
in 1992. 
</P>
</TEXT>
