<HEADLINE> Italy Sticks to NATO's Hard Line on Yugoslavia's </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, April 6 (Xinhua) -- Italian government stuck firmly to
NATO's hard line on Yugoslavia's Easter truce in the southern
province of Kosovo, saying Tuesday evening that the move fell far
short of what was needed to call off bombings.
</P>
<P>
NATO said Tuesday evening that the unilateral truce declared by
Yugoslavia at 8:00 pm of April 6 was not enough to halt air
attacks.
</P>
<P>
Italian Prime Minister Massimo D'Alema said at the same time
that "I shall hold the view of our allies, and Belgrade's
temporary truce appears insufficient to start a peaceful
resolution of the conflict."
</P>
<P>
He called on Belgrade to go further, following its first step
with "weightier and more significant commitments including
acceptance of an international presence in Kosovo to protect
returning refugees."
</P>
<P>
D'Alema said NATO needed to see these things happening before
it could launch a peace initiative, adding that the announcement
of a truce is step in the right direction.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the ruling Party of Italian Communists and the
Greens both said the truce was a chink of light offering a chance
for diplomacy to come to the fore. Both parties urged D'Alema to
make sure the chance was not wasted.
</P>
<P>
"Once again the U.S. is trying to impose its line," said the
Italian Communists' leader Armando Cossutta, "this is a positive
signal that mustn't be thrown away."
</P>
<P>
The Italian government's tough stance was mirrored in other
European capitals, with similar statements coming from France,
Germany, and Britain. 
</P>
