<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: Uganda Beefs up Efforts Against Corruption by Feng Jian, Wang Shangzhi </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, April 6 (Xinhua) -- Ugandan President Yoweri Museveni,
in a surprise move late Monday night, axed several ministers in
the latest major cabinet reshuffle, marking the government's
intensifying efforts against rampant corruption among senior
government officials.
</P>
<P>
The last-minute decision to drop the long-serving ministers was
made in response to mounting pressure from the parliament and an
indignant outcry from the general public for the government to
stem corruption among the ruling elite.
</P>
<P>
Vice President Specioza Kazibwe, who was dropped from the
agricultural portfolio, was the most eye-catching because she has
been accused by a parliamentary select committee of failing to
supervise the famous valley dam project which caused the
government to lose 3.4 billion shillings (3.4 million U.S.
dollars) and is likely to face censure from parliament this week.
</P>
<P>
Sam Kutesa, former state minister in charge of planning and
investment, was kicked out this time because he was recently
censured by the parliament on charges of influence peddling and
abuse of office in the country's privatization process.
</P>
<P>
It had been widely believed that President Museveni will
stretch@out a helping hand to this struggling minister because
their wives are sisters. But this intimacy with the First Family
did not save the sinking minister.
</P>
<P>
Tom Butime, former minister of internal affairs, was moved to
chair the Ministry of Disaster Preparedness and Refugees.
</P>
<P>
Analysts here observed that his transfer implies Museveni's
dissatisfaction with the security situation in the country and
anger at the revealed corruption among top police bosses.
</P>
<P>
The Bwindi massacre, in which eight foreign tourists were
killed in a national park in western Uganda in early March,
triggered widening local and international concerns about security
in this land-locked country where tourism industry is still young.
</P>
<P>
This incident caused many foreign tourists to cancel their
plans to Uganda. A big U.S. business delegation rescinded their
decision to participate in an international trade fair here due to
security concerns.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, former Inspector General of Police John Odomel was
forced to resign following an investigation report which
discovered that his own companies were doing business with the
police through illegal means.
</P>
<P>
More recently, Chris Bakiiza, director of Criminal
Investigation Department, is being probed for bribery, corruption
and negligence of duty and is very likely to be removed.
</P>
<P>
This shows that the government is unflinching efforts against
corruption.
</P>
<P>
But this reshuffle is not the end of the fight. The parliament
is still working to curb corruption among ministers and other
senior officials.
</P>
<P>
Considering this cabinet reshuffle not enough to check
corruption in the Ministry of Agriculture, Animal Industry and
Fisheries, the parliament was still debating the report by the
select committee Tuesday afternoon and considering what to do
next.
</P>
<P>
Many members of parliament hold that two of the state ministers
who were mentioned in the report and should be dropped are still
ministers: one is still in the ministry while the other
transferred to another portfolio.
</P>
<P>
Therefore, they think this reshuffle is by no means fatal to
corruption in the ministry. So they decided to continue debating
the report and to censure the ministers if evidence suffices.
</P>
<P>
Whether the parliament will censure the two ministers or not,
one thing is for sure. That is, they will continue on the crusade
against corruption. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990407.0060 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-07 </DATE_TIME>
