<HEADLINE> U.S. Says It Will House Kosovo Refugees at Base </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, April 6 (Xinhua) -- The United States announced on
Tuesday that it will temporarily house 20,000 Kosovo refugees away
from the U.S. mainland at its naval base at Guantanamo Bay, Cuba.
</P>
<P>
It would take several days before the refugees will begin being
transported from the Balkans to the site in Cuba, said White House
spokesman Joe Lockhart.
</P>
<P>
Lockhart said the base was chosen because of its ability to
house a large number of people quickly.
</P>
<P>
"This action is intended... in combination with our NATO
allies, to assist front-line states such as Macedonia in dealing
with the tremendous burden they have incurred in recent days with
the flow of refugees out of Kosovo," Lockhart said.
</P>
<P>
"This facility will be temporary, as we fully intend the
Kosovars will ultimately return to their homes and the operation
will only transport people voluntarily," he said.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Kosovo refugees who are already in the United States
but lacking valid immigration status will be allowed to remain
under a temporary protected status, said the spokesman.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. Justice Department would extend the cutoff date for
eligibility to cover Kosovo refugees in the United States as of
this month, as opposed to the current cutoff of June 1998, he
added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
