<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Yugoslavia's Peace Proposal Rejected by NATO </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, April 6 (Xinhua) -- The North Atlantic Treaty
Organization (NATO) Tuesday formally refused to accept
Yugoslavia's peace proposal as the NATO chief said the cease-fire
offer "is clearly insufficient."
</P>
<P>
NATO Secretary-General Javier Solana said in a statement that
the unilateral cease-fire proposed by the Yugoslav and Serbian
governments did not meet NATO's demand. "Before a cease-fire can
be considered, President Milosevic must meet the demands
established by the international community," he said.
</P>
<P>
The NATO head said the current military action against
Yugoslavia is in support of the political aims of the
international community: a peaceful multi-ethnic democratic Kosovo
in which all its people live in security.
</P>
<P>
"These aims can be achieved by the return of all refugees and
therefore the deployment of an international security presence,
the withdrawal of Serb military, police and paramilitary forces,
and putting into place of a political framework for Kosovo on the
basis of the Rambouillet Accords," Solana said in conclusion.
</P>
<P>
Earlier, the Yugoslav government declared a unilateral
cease-fire in Kosovo starting at 8 p.m. local time in observance
of the Orthodox Easter holiday. Yugoslavia's offers include a
unilateral cease-fire, early peace talks and arrangement of
refugees' return. However, the United States, leader of NATO,
immediately rejected the proposal and vowed to continue attacks
against Yugoslavia. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
