<DOCNO> XIE19990407.0067 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bangkok Bank Boosts Capital Adequacy Ratio </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, April 7 (Xinhua) -- Bangkok Bank Plc, Thailand's
biggest commercial bank, has boosted its capital adequacy ratio
above the central bank's requirement by raising 46 billion baht
(1.2 billion U.S. dollars) from the market.
</P>
<P>
Bank President Chartsiri Sophonpanitch said Wednesday that the
bank's tier-1 capital adequacy ratio was raised to 13.7 percent,
more than three times above the central bank's minimum
requirement.
</P>
<P>
He said the money was raised through the issue of Capital
Augmented Preference Securities (CAPS).
</P>
<P>
The CAPS subscriptions included 6 percent from foreign
investors and 70 percent from individuals, with the balance being
held by provident funds and other institutions.
</P>
<P>
The news pushed up shares of Bangkok Bank by 2.8 percent to
55.5 baht (1.5 dollars) Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Money raised through the issue would cover non-performing loans
(NPLs) and meet the government's tough new provisioning rules.
Thai banking and finance sectors have NPLs estimated at 2.73
trillion baht (73 billion dollars), more than 45 percent of total
loans.
</P>
<P>
"We are extremely pleased with the positive response to the
issue... which demonstrates the broad level of confidence Thai
investors continue to have in the bank," Chartsiri said.
</P>
<P>
"Many investors recognize the financial stability and long-term
prospects of Bangkok Bank and view CAPS as a chance to be part of
our expanding business as we work through the recession and
towards a brighter future," he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
