<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Security Council Holds Consultations on Iraq </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, April 7 (Xinhua) -- The United Nations Security
Council is scheduled to hold consultations Wednesday morning in a
bid to forge its new policy towards Iraq.
</P>
<P>
The Security Council, sharply divided after the U.S.-led air
strikes against Iraq last December, will first be briefed by Celso
Amorim, the chairman of the three panels on Iraq established
according to a January 30 note by the Council.
</P>
<P>
The three panels have presented their reports on the
assessments on Iraq's disarmament, humanitarian situation and
returning of Kuwait's property to the Security Council, which will
be the basis for the Council to form its new policy towards Iraq.
</P>
<P>
The first panel, on disarmament and current and future ongoing
monitoring and verification issues, recommended that intrusive
inspections under a monitoring program be needed to resume in
Iraq. It also called for a renovated or restructured U.N. Special
Commission (UNSCOM), now responsible for dismantling Iraq's
weapons of mass destruction.
</P>
<P>
The second panel, on humanitarian situation, recommended
improvement and some alterations to the U.N. humanitarian
program, which allows Iraq to sell limited amounts of oil to
provide humanitarian aid for its people. It also suggested the
Council consider authorizing foreign investment to improve Iraq's
export abilities.
</P>
<P>
The third panel, on prisoners of war and Kuwaiti property,
concluded that Iraq had not provided sufficient explanations about
missing Kuwaitis or cooperated enough in returning looted
property.
</P>
<P>
It is widely seen here that Iraq will most likely reject any
proposals for renewed U.N. relations that does not include lifting
of the sanctions, which has been in the place since its invasion
of Kuwait in 1990.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
