<BODY>
<HEADLINE> HK Customs Officers Seize Counterfeit Cigarettes </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, April 7 (Xinhua) -- Hong Kong Customs officers
seized about 17 million sticks of counterfeit cigarettes worth 9.3
million HK dollars (1.2 million U.S. dollars) last Thursday, a
spokesman for the Customs and Excise Department said today.
</P>
<P>
Acting on information, officers of the Intellectual Property
Investigation Bureau took prompt action and intercepted at a Kwai
Chung container terminal two containers shipped from Manila, the
Philippines, via Singapore, and made the seizure.
</P>
<P>
Subsequent investigations led to the arrest of two men and a
Singaporean woman, aged from 29 to 52.
</P>
<P>
The seized cigarettes were destined for Taiwan, said the
spokesman.
</P>
<P>
Customs officers have this year seized 35 million sticks of
counterfeit cigarettes worth more than 19 million HK dollars (2.44
million U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
Last year, the officers seized 13 million sticks of fake
cigarettes worth 7.3 million HK dollars (940,000 U.S. dollars). In
addition, the officers last year also seized counterfeit products,
including clothing and watches, worth 52 million HK dollars (6.67
million U.S. dollars), and arrested 760 suspects.
</P>
<P>
According to the Trade Descriptions Ordinance, anyone found in
possession of false trade descriptions goods for business or
commercial purpose, is liable to prosecution, and the maximum
penalty for the offense is a fine of 500,000 HK dollars (64,100 U.
S. dollars) and five years' imprisonment upon conviction.
</P>
<P>
"Customs would continue enforcement actions against all
counterfeiting and piracy activities in an effort to protect the
good image of Hong Kong," the spokesman said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
