<HEADLINE> Cypriot Government Backs Speaker's Mission to </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, April 7 (Xinhua) -- Cypriot Foreign Minister Ioannis
Kasoulides said Wednesday that the government will provide every
assistance to House Speaker Spyros Kyprianou in his mission to
Yugoslavia to seek the release of three American soldiers.
</P>
<P>
Kasoulides wished Kyprianou "success," hoping the speaker will
"return with the three American soldiers," who were captured by
Serb forces last week near Macedonian-Yugoslav border.
</P>
<P>
The soldiers were part of the troops dispatched by the North
Atlantic Treaty Organization (NATO) as potential peacekeeping
troops to Kosovo once Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic
accepts a peace deal.
</P>
<P>
NATO has been bombing Serb targets since March 24 with a
claimed aim of stopping Milosevic from killing
independence-seeking ethnic Albanians in the Yugoslav province of
Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
Kasoulides clarified that the Cypriot government was not asked
to make the effort and it was a personal initiative of Kyprianou.
</P>
<P>
Kyprianou said earlier that he will be going to Belgrade
Wednesday afternoon to meet Milosevic and conclude an arrangement
for the release of the three U.S. prisoners of war.
</P>
<P>
Kyprianou revealed that he will "bring them back to Cyprus and
will give them to the American authorities."
</P>
<P>
He said the Cypriot government will "not get involved in
negotiations for a political solution" and that the involvement
is based only "on humanitarian grounds."
</P>
<P>
However, he said if Milosevic asks Cyprus to become involved
in a political settlement, "then I shall see how we can handle
it and we can discuss." 
</P>
