<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's Second Largest Copper Mine Inaugurated </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 7 (Xinhua) -- A company to develop China's
second largest copper mine in China was set up here today in the
country's northwestern Xinjiang Uyger Autonomous Region.
</P>
<P>
The mine, located in Ashele in northern Xinjiang, is planned to
produce 23,000 tons of copper and more than 10,000 tons of zinc a
year with a life circle of 35 years.
</P>
<P>
Wang Zhonghui, chairman of the Ashele Copper Corporation Ltd.,
said this copper mine will help ease the country's copper shortage.
</P>
<P>
China now imports a large amount of copper annually, and has
discovered only two major copper mines in the past 15 years.
</P>
<P>
The Ashele copper mine was discovered in 1984, with total
copper deposits of 1.08 million tons. The other newly discovered
copper mine is in Zijinshan in east China's Fujian Province. The
largest copper mine in China is in Dexing in Jiangxi Province.
</P>
<P>
China took ten years to survey and prepare the establishment of
the Ashele copper mine, and investment for the first phase of
development amounts to 870 million yuan. The first phase includes
ore-selecting projects, and copper refineries will be built on the
site of the mine after the ore-selecting projects become
profitable.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
