<DOCNO> XIE19990407.0076 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.N. Arrangement for Lockerbie Handover Kept Secret </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, April 7 (Xinhua) -- The United Nations
operation to arrangement the transfer of the two Lockerbie
suspects for a trial before a Scottish court in the Netherlands
"was intricate, complex and above all secret, "New York Times," a
widely-circulated newspaper in the United States, said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
"No one except Hans Corell, the chief legal counsel for the
United Nations -- not even Secretary-General Kofi Annan -- knew
the details surrounding the logistics for the surrender of the two
Libyan suspects charged with planting the bomb that downed Pan Am
Flight 103 over Lockerbie, Scotland," a bylined story, carried by
the New York-based newspaper, said.
</P>
<P>
Last October and November, United Nations lawyers led by Corell
and a Libyan legal team led by Kamel Hassan Maghur, the former
Libyan foreign minister, met quietly at the United Nations over
several weeks to "clarify" the many thorny questions: Who would be
authorized to defend the Libyans in a Scottish court of law in the
Netherlands? Would the suspects be considered "passengers" or
"prisoners" on the flight from Libya?
</P>
<P>
"It's one thing to work with the technicians and another to get
a political decision," Annan said. "And we needed a political
decision, which is why I went to work."
</P>
<P>
In early December last year, Annan flew to Libyan for a meeting
with Libyan leader Muammar el-Gaddfai, but he failed to persuade
Tripoli into surrendering the two suspects.
</P>
<P>
South Africa and Saudi Arabia later joined the United Nations
in the diplomatic mediation to smooth the way for the transfer.
</P>
<P>
The president of the U.N. Security Council, Alain Dejammet of
France, Monday announced the suspension of sanctions imposed on
Libya after Annan formally reported that the two suspects had
arrived in the Netherlands for the trial.
</P>
<P>
The bombing of the American airline over the Scottish town of
Lockerbie killed a total of 270 people.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990407.0077 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Key Points of Bangladesh's New Industrial Policy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, April 7 (Xinhua) -- Bangladesh's new industrial policy,
which was officially announced Wednesday, has 16 main features
designed to accelerate the pace of industrialization in the
country through boosting the private sector and attracting foreign
direct investment.
</P>
<P>
The following are the highlights of the five-year industrial
policy, which was approved by the government Monday:
</P>
<P>
-- The policy envisages a 25-percent contribution of the
industrial sector to the gross domestic product (GDP) over a
period of 10 years. It is also designed to employ 20 percent of
the country's total manpower;
</P>
<P>
-- To build up a dynamic private sector which will play a
significant role in industrialization and investment. The
government's role in this regard would be that of a facilitator
instead of the regulator for encouraging local and foreign
investment;
</P>
<P>
-- To encourage foreign direct investment for setting up
export-oriented as well as domestic market-oriented industries;
</P>
<P>
-- To provide incentives for the setting up of labor-intensive,
small and cottage industries that would open up more employment
opportunities for woman through developing their skills;
</P>
<P>
-- Proper utilization of the production capacity of the
existing industries;
</P>
<P>
-- Improvement of indigenous technology and setting up of
industrial units that would use domestic raw materials;
</P>
<P>
-- Diversification of industrial goods and rapid increase of
the volume of exports;
</P>
<P>
-- There would be no differences between local and foreign
investments and steps would be taken for promoting regional and
sub-regional cooperation;
</P>
<P>
-- Institutional rules and regulations would be simplified for
boosting the private sector and foreign investment by removing
bottlenecks in this regard;
</P>
<P>
-- Capital market would be strengthened though increasing
domestic savings and foreign investment;
</P>
<P>
-- Improvement of port facilities, and development of power,
transport and communication infrastructure. Special incentives for
small and cottage industries would be given;
</P>
<P>
-- Development of service sectors as well as local
sub-contracting industries;
</P>
<P>
-- Setting up of coordinated information management center and
providing financial and technical assistance for agro-based
industries;
</P>
<P>
-- Present policy for privatizing the state-owned enterprises
would be vigorously pursued;
</P>
<P>
-- Anomalies with regard to fixation of duties and taxes
between the public and private sectors would be removed; and
</P>
<P>
-- Tax holidays ranging from five to seven years would be
provided for different industries, depending on their respective
condition. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990407.0078 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-07 </DATE_TIME>
