<HEADLINE> Xinhua World News Summary at 1600 GMT, April 7 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ATHENS -- Greek government spokesman Dimitris Reppas confirmed
Wednesday that Yugoslavia has agreed to release the three U.S.
marines captured last week near the border of Macedonia.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a press briefing, Reppas said that acting Cyprus
President Spyros Kyprianou, invited by Yugoslav President Slobodan
Milosevic, will go to Belgrade to take back the U.S. soldiers.
</P>
<P>
The Greek government will help the soldiers leave Belgrade, he
added.
</P>
<P>
Well-informed sources here said that the three Americans would
first be sent to the Cypriot capital of Nicosia possibly later
Wednesday, where the Cyprus government would hand them over to the
U.S. embassy there. (Greece-Yugoslavia-US Marines)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
LONDON -- British Prime Minister Tony Blair said on Wednesday
that Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic must agree to NATO's
terms before the airstrikes are called off.
</P>
<P>
Speaking to British Sky Television, Blair said that Yugoslav
troops must withdraw from Kosovo and an international force be
allowed in to oversee a peace agreement.
</P>
<P>
"He has to agree to NATO's terms... That means he gets his
forces out of Kosovo, he allows an international force in and
these people are allowed to return to their homes in peace. Those
are the terms that must be obeyed for this (air) campaign to cease,
" he said.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Blair insisted again that there was no split in the
NATO alliance after more than two weeks of airstrikes. (Britain-
Yugoslavia)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS -- The United Nations Security Council is
scheduled to hold consultations Wednesday morning in a bid to
forge its new policy towards Iraq.
</P>
<P>
The Security Council, sharply divided after the U.S.-led air
strikes against Iraq last December, will first be briefed by Celso
Amorim, the chairman of the three panels on Iraq established
according to a January 30 note by the Council.
</P>
<P>
The three panels have presented their reports on the
assessments on Iraq's disarmament, humanitarian situation and
