<BODY>
<HEADLINE> New Strain of Influenza A Virus Discovered in HK </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, April 7 (Xinhua) -- A new strain of influenza A
virus (H9N2) has been discovered from two patients by the Virus
Unit of the Hong Kong Department of Health.
</P>
<P>
The two patients are girls aged one and four who recovered
fully from influenza-like illnesses last month.
</P>
<P>
A typical influenza virus was picked up from their clinical
specimens of throat secretion by the enhanced influenza
surveillance system set up to monitor the avian flu situation in
Hong Kong since late 1997.
</P>
<P>
Results available today confirmed that the virus was influenza
A (H9N2).
</P>
<P>
The specimens were sent to the World Health Organization (WHO)
Influenza Collaborating Reference Laboratories in the United
Kingdom and the United States for further identification.
</P>
<P>
"This is the first time H9N2 virus, an avian influenza virus,
is isolated from humans in Hong Kong," Deputy Director of Health
Dr. Paul Saw said Wednesday at a press briefing.
</P>
<P>
This virus is sensitive to the drugs amantadine and remantadine,
he said.
</P>
<P>
According to him, influenza A (H9N2) has been isolated from
duck and chicken for many years.
</P>
<P>
"Detailed investigations are underway to find out how the
patients contracted the virus," Saw said.
</P>
<P>
The Department of Health's special investigation team on avian
influenza will work closely with local and overseas experts to
assess the global health impact of this new discovery and its mode
of transmission, he said.
</P>
<P>
With the experience gained in the control of the avian flu
outbreak in late 1997, the department would be better equipped to
coordinate efforts from international health authorities and local
experts to monitor and control the situation, he said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990407.0082 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Vice Premier Urges Fight Against Forest Fire </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 7 (Xinhua) -- Chinese Vice Premier Wen Jiabao
has called on the local people to quickly put out the forest fire
in north China's Shanxi province and safeguard people's lives.
</P>
<P>
A total of 23 people were killed while fighting the fire and 22,
000 hectares of forest are threatened by the fire which broke out
near the city of Fenyang on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Wen asked local officials to carefully organize and wisely
direct efforts to fight the blaze to avoid human casualties.
</P>
<P>
He asked the State Forestry Administration to issue an urgent
circular to all local authorities in the country on Tuesday,
instructing them to pay greater attention to preventing forest
fires, and urged people to take all possible measures to
extinguish the Fenyang fire quickly and prevent any reoccurrence.
</P>
<P>
Strong winds forced fire-fighters to cease operations on the
northern side of the burning area today, but people are bringing
the fire under control on the southern and eastern sides.
</P>
<P>
More than 2,000 people are currently at work attempting to put
out the flames. The State Forestry Administration has called in
over 200 forest police from neighboring Inner Mongolia to assist
with the fire-fighting today.
</P>
<P>
Experts were also busy preparing to make artificial rain to
bring the fire under control.  
</P>
</TEXT>
