<DOCNO> XIE19990407.0090 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bangladesh Unveils New Industrial Policy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, April 7 (Xinhua) -- The Bangladeshi government Wednesday
announced its new industrial policy which pledges equal treatment
to both domestic and foreign investors while undertaking ventures.
</P>
<P>
Highlighting the salient features of the five-year industrial
policy which was approved by the cabinet Monday, Commerce and
Industries Minister Tofail Ahmed said that no difference would be
made between domestic and foreign investors.
</P>
<P>
The policy adopted the strategy of simplification of relevant
rules and regulations for creating a conducive and productive
private sector that would play the pivotal role in
industrialization and investment in the country, Ahmed told a
press conference.
</P>
<P>
"All the regulatory obstacles will be removed for attracting
more domestic and foreign direct investment," he said.
</P>
<P>
The government would play the role of facilitator instead of
regulator to encourage foreign and local investment, according to
the minister.
</P>
<P>
Priority would be attached to setting up small and medium
industries and creating scope for massive employment
opportunities, including those for women in labor-intensive
sectors, he added.
</P>
<P>
The new industrial policy, identifying 16 thrust sectors, would
come into force as soon as the relevant laws have been passed,
said Ahmed. The sectors include agro-based industries, artificial
flower production, computer and software and information
technology, electronics, frozen food, floriculture, gift items,
infrastructure, jute goods, jewelry and diamond, leather, oil and
gas, sericulture and silk industries, stuffed toys, textiles and
tourism.
</P>
<P>
The tax holiday for the industries would range from five to
seven years according to their location.
</P>
<P>
The minister noted that top priority would be attached to the
implementation of the policy which, with the passage of time,
would be reviewed to suit the changing scenario.
</P>
<P>
For the successful implementation of the policy, the minister
sought unstinted support and cooperation from all, particularly
from the opposition political parties. "There might be differences
of opinion but there should be consensus on some points of common
national interest," he said.
</P>
<P>
According to the new industrial policy, the country's
industrial sector would be able to contribute to 25 percent of the
gross domestic product in the next 10 years, instead of the
current 10 percent, and would employ some 20 percent of the
country's manpower during the same period. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
