<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.N. to Supply More Food to Refugees in Zambia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, April 7 (Xinhua) -- The third dispatch of food will be
sent to refugee camps at Kaputa in Northern Province of Zambia
Thursday, bringing the total of relief food to 362 tons since
March 17, a senior official of the World Food Program said here
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Bai Bojang, WFP Deputy Country Director in Zambia, said that
food aid needs to be quickly mobilized and delivered to the
northern border area in order to feed a growing number of refugees
crossing over from the Democratic Republic of Congo (DRC).
</P>
<P>
The latest figures indicate that at least 20,000 refugees have
crossed from the DRC into the district of Kaputa since March 5,
with more expected to arrive as a result of continual heavy
fighting between the DRC government troops and the rebels.
</P>
<P>
A recent WFP mission to Kaputa area verified that the flow of
people has not abated, with the number reaching Kaputa as many as
500 people.
</P>
<P>
"At this rate, we could easily see another 15,000 people
arriving within a month," said Techeste Zergaber, WFP Country
Director in Zambia.
</P>
<P>
The WFP has been able to borrow food from other programs to
feed the refugees, but those supplies are rapidly becoming
exhausted, he noted.
</P>
<P>
"We will soon be launching an appeal to donors to help us
respond to this latest crisis," he said.
</P>
<P>
The nutritional condition of the refugees is currently not
cause for concern, said Zergaber, apart from some emaciation due
to the long distances travelled. It was recommended, however,
that a nutritional survey be quickly undertaken to identify any
special needs of women and children, who form at least 60 percent
of the population and are typically the most vulnerable.
</P>
<P>
Some cases of measles have also been reported, and outbreaks of
malaria, diarrhoea and cholera are feared as the area is
mosquito-infested and clean water supplies are problematic, he
said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990407.0095 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> EDS-UPDATE Yugoslavia Agrees to Free Captured U.S. Marines: Greece </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ATHENS, April 7 (Xinhua) -- Greek government spokesman Dimitris
Reppas confirmed Wednesday that Yugoslavia has agreed to release
the three U.S. marines captured last week near the border of
Macedonia.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a press briefing, Reppas said that acting Cyprus
President Spyros Kyprianou, invited by Yugoslav President Slobodan
Milosevic, will go to Belgrade to take back the U.S. soldiers.
</P>
<P>
The Greek government will help the soldiers leave Belgrade, he
added.
</P>
<P>
Well-informed sources here said that the three Americans would
first be sent to the Cypriot capital of Nicosia possibly later
Wednesday, where the Cyprus government would hand them over to the
U.S. embassy there.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Reppas renewed Greece's calls for a political
solution to the Kosovo crisis.
</P>
<P>
As a member of the North Atlantic Treaty Organization (NATO) as
well as the European Union, Greece refused to participate in
NATO's military actions against Yugoslavia. And Athens has
repeated that it could mediate between Belgrade and NATO for a
peaceful solution to the Kosovo crisis. 
</P>
</TEXT>
