<HEADLINE> EU Mideast Envoy Visits Lebanon on Peace Process </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, April 7 (Xinhua) -- The European Union (EU) Middle East
Envoy Miguel Moratinos arrived here Wednesday for talks with
Lebanese leaders on the stalled peace process in the region.
</P>
<P>
Moratinos, who came from Syria by land, is due to meet with
Lebanese President Emile Lahoud, Prime Minister Salim Hoss and
House Speaker Nabih Berri on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Upon his arrival at the Lebanese border town of Masnaa, the
envoy reiterated the role the EU will play to help achieve a
comprehensive and just peace in the region.
</P>
<P>
Peace talks between Syria, Lebanon and Israel have been
non-existent since the hardline Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin
Netanyahu came to power in June, 1996.
</P>
<P>
Israel is occupying a swath of land in south Lebanon where it
set up a self-styled security zone in 1985 with the claimed aim of
protecting its north from Lebanese guerrillas' cross-border
attacks.
</P>
<P>
It refuses to return the Golan Heights it captured from Syria
during the 1967 Middle East war.
</P>
<P>
During his two-day visit, Moratinos will also discuss
preparations for the upcoming Euro-Mediterranean forum, which will
be held at foreign ministerial level this month in Stuttgart,
Germany.
</P>
<P>
The forum will address the cooperation between 15 EU member
states and 12 countries along the southern and eastern
Mediterranean coast in the fields of economy, culture, security
and politics.
</P>
<P>
Lebanon will send a senior official to participate in the
session. 
</P>
</TEXT>
