<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Big Powers Work on Adaptation of Rambouillet Accord: France </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, April 7 (Xinhua) -- French Foreign Minister Hubert
Vedrine said on Wednesday that big powers are working on the
adaptation of the Rambouillet peace plan for Kosovo, because of
the mass exodus of Kosovo Albanians.
</P>
<P>
"At one moment or another, we should implement a political
solution, which has been blocked stubbornly for months by (
Yugoslav) President Milosevic," Vedrine told Radio Info.
</P>
<P>
While rejecting a ceasefire proposal by Yugoslavia on Tuesday,
NATO insists that Belgrade accept a five-point plan, including the
return of refugees, the withdrawal of Yugoslav forces, the signing
of the Rambouillet agreement, and the deployment of a NATO force
in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
"There is a work on this political solution: On the basis of
the agreements of Rambouillet, what should be adapted? What
should be kept? What form should the international security on
the ground take?" said the French foreign minister.
</P>
<P>
He again described the truce proposal for the Orthodox Easter
by Belgrade as "absolutely insufficient."
</P>
<P>
"The diplomatic efforts aim to seek a political solution, when
we are back in this field. But for the moment, unfortunately,
there is no sign of any kind from the authorities of Belgrade, and
it is for this the military operations will continue," said
Vedrine.
</P>
<P>
He said that the Group of Eight (G8) most industrialized
nations, the Contact Group on former Yugoslavia, and the foreign
ministers of NATO will have consultations on adapting the
Rambouillet peace plans, which was named after the French chateau
50 kilometers southwest of Paris where the talks on Kosovo were
held in February.
</P>
<P>
"In France, we think that the Security Council at this moment
should also play a key role," he added.
</P>
<P>
The Rambouillet peace plan, adopted by the Kosovo Albanians but
rejected by the Serbs, calls for substantial autonomy in Kosovo
and the deployment of NATO troops there. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
