<HEADLINE> Senior Chinese Official on Health of the Elderly </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 7 (Xinhua) -- Chinese Vice Premier Li Lanqing
released a statement today on the occasion of the 50th World
Health Day calling on all of society to provide fair and equal
living opportunities for the elderly.
</P>
<P>
Li stressed that old people should be given greater economic
support and better medical treatment and health services, and that
they should be given adequate health information for healthier and
more satisfying lives.
</P>
<P>
He said the World Health Organization has chosen "active and
healthy aging" as the theme of this year's Health Day, indicating
that the issue of the elderly has gained the general attention of
the international community.
</P>
<P>
"Initiating 'active aging' is very significant for China, which
is home of the world's largest elder population," he said.
</P>
<P>
He said that China has a long history of respecting and loving
the elderly, and the Communist Party and the government have
always paid attention to issues affecting elderly people.
</P>
<P>
He called for concerted efforts on the part of everyone to
create a social environment that is fair and equal to all ages.
</P>
<P>
Official statistics show that China has the largest elderly
population in the world, with 120 million people over 60 years of
age and nine million 80 years old or more.
</P>
<P>
Experts predict that the number of elderly Chinese will reach
more than 400 million by the middle of the next century. 
</P>
</TEXT>
