<BODY>
<HEADLINE> South Korea to Seek Interpol's Help to Catch Criminals </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, April 7 (Xinhua) -- The South Korean National Police
Agency Wednesday said it will seek the help of Interpol to catch
and extradite more than 400 South Korean criminals hiding out in
foreign countries.
</P>
<P>
More than 380, or 86 percent, of the 443 wanted criminals are
charged with white-collar crimes, such as fraud, embezzlement and
the issuance of bad checks while eleven of the men are wanted on
charges of murder.
</P>
<P>
The total amount of financial damages they have inflicted adds
up to 890 billion won (about 730 million U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
The criminals are believed to be staying in 31 countries, with
267 staying in the United States.
</P>
<P>
Of the criminals, 223, or 58.3 percent, fled the country after
South Korea was hit by the economic crisis in November 1997.
</P>
<P>
Since 1990, a total of 495 Korean criminals, who fled to
foreign countries, have been repatriated back to South Korea.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
