<HEADLINE> Second-seed Rafter Ousted in First Round </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, April 7 (Xinhua) -- the Second-seeded Patrick Rafter
suffered a frist-round clash when the Australian was upset by
German Bernd Karbacher in the 350,000 U.S. dollar Hong Kong Open
here on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Karbacher rallied strongly to win the first-set game 6-7 (4-7),
7-6 (7-1), 6-2.
</P>
<P>
Rafter, the two-time defending U.S. Open champion, struggled to
find his feet on the hardcourt. The world No. 5 blamed his loss on
poor serving.
</P>
<P>
After trading tie-breaks in the first two sets, Karbacher
turned on the pressure in the decisive third set as Rafter slumped.
The German, ranked 117 in the world, broke Rafter twice to romp to
victory.
</P>
<P>
Cedric Pioline of France was another casualty among seeded
players as the fourth seed was beaten 2-6, 6-1, 6-4 by Italy's
Laurence Tieleman in the first round.
</P>
<P>
World No. 4 Richard Krajicek of the Netherlands survived a
shaky start before moving in to the second round with a 6-4, 6-4
victory over Japan's No. 1 and world No. 10 Takao Suzuki.
</P>
<P>
American Andre Agassi hardly broke a sweat as he rushed to a 6-
2, 6-2 victory over Italy's Gianluca Pozzi.
</P>
<P>
Top seed Krajicek too admitted Wednesday that he had problems
getting accustomed to the faster surface in Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
The Dutch survived five break points in his first set against
Suzuki. One break of service in each set was all it took for
Krajicek to enter the second round, where he will meet defending
champion Kenneth Carlsen of Denmark. 
</P>
</TEXT>
