<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: Israel in Predicament Over Kosovo Crisis </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, April 7 (Xinhua) -- The Israeli Knesset (parliament)
is scheduled to discuss the Kosovo crisis next week as asked by
the Meretz Party leader Yossi Sarid. It remains uncertain whether
the Knesset would adopt a clear-cut resulotion supporting the
NATO's action in Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
The Israeli government has refrained from giving explicit
support to the NATO's actions though the North Atlantic Treaty
Organization has launched its airstrikes aganist Yugoslavia for
two weeks.
</P>
<P>
Only after sustained criticism by the press of the Israeli
ambiguity over the Kosovo crisis did Prime Minister Benjamin
Netanyahu and his office voiced condemnation of massacres by the
Serbs or any other group.
</P>
<P>
But Foreign Minister Ariel Sharon has repeatedly aired his
objection to the NATO air riads, warning Israel could be the next
target some day in the future if Israel supports NATO's action.
</P>
<P>
Several days ago, the Meretz party leader blamed the government
for neither condemning the "genocide" of the Kosovo Albanians
committed by the Yugoslav government, nor openly supporting NATO's
airstrikes.
</P>
<P>
Sarid called for a special Knesset session to discuss the
Kosovo crisis so that Israel can adopt a clear-cut attitude toward
the Kosovo issue. He also urged the government to accept some of
the Kosovo refugees.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Sarid crticized Sharon's remarks against the NATO
airstrikes, saying Sharon's attitude can only jeopardize Israel's
foreign policy.
</P>
<P>
Sharon, now in the United States, is reportedly to meet
U.S. Secretary of State Madelaine Albright soon and explain to
her what the Israeli side is thinking about the Kosovo crisis.
</P>
<P>
But as victims of the deadliest genocide in the 20th century,
Jews here in Israel do feel a special moral resonance in
astrocities committed against ethinic minorities in Europe.
</P>
<P>
In fact, the current crisis in Kosovo is regarded with
ambivalence among the Israelis, some of whom are deeply uneasy
with the NATO bombing campaign against the Yugoslav Serbs.
</P>
<P>
History-minded Israelis know that the Serbs stood up against
the Nazis and eventually beated them back during the World War II,
at great cost in blood. But the Kosovoar Albanians, by contrast,
joined a German division toward the end of the War.
</P>
<P>
And to some Israelis, such as Sharon, the plight of the
Kosovoar Albanians bears enough resemblance to that of the
Palestinians, or Israel's own million-strong Arab minority.
</P>
<P>
Like Israeli Arabs, the ethnic Albanians in Kosovo are a
Muslim minority in a sovereign state. Like the Palestinians, they
aspire to create an independent state on land they regard as
their birthright.
</P>
<P>
What a resolution the Knesset will adopt remains to be seen.

07/04/99 13:29 GMT

NNNN
21:34 21:34 g # PAB
</P>
</TEXT>
