<HEADLINE> India Calls For Single Currency In South Asian </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, April 7 (Xinhua) -- Indian Commerce Minister
Ramakrishna Hegde Wednesday called for a single currency in South
Asia, saying that it would help turn the impoverished region into
a powerful trading block.
</P>
<P>
Hegde said in Bombay that the seven-nation South Asian
Association for Region Cooperation (SAARC) should follow the
example of the European Union (EU) and have a single currency like
the euro.
</P>
<P>
"Like the European Union, we need to work on a common currency
and forge closer ties for trade and commerce," Hegde told an
annual meeting of the SAARC Chamber of Commerce and Industry.
</P>
<P>
He said that his country would remove all import restrictions
to goods from the SAARC countries if other six countries would
also do so in a phased manner by the end of 2000.
</P>
<P>
SAARC comprises Bangladesh, Bhutan, India, Nepal, Pakistan, the
Maldives and Sri Lanka. 
</P>
</TEXT>
