<HEADLINE> Prospects for Future Sino-Syrian Cooperation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAMASCUS, April 7 (Xinhua) -- The prospects for the future
development of trade and economic cooperation between China and
Syria are bright, and China is willing to further strengthen the
cooperative relations betwee the two countries, China's top
legislator Li Peng said here on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Li, who arrived here Tuesday evening on a three-day official
visit, made the statement during his talks with Syrian Prime
Minister Mahmoud Zouebi.
</P>
<P>
Li Peng, chairman of the Standing Committee of the National
People's Congress (parliament) of China, highly evaluated the
development of the bilateral ties since the two countries
established diplomatic relations in 1956.
</P>
<P>
The friendly relations of cooperation between China and Syria
have been developing steadily, featuring ever expanding bilateral
cooperation in the political, economic, science and technological,
and cultural fields, he noted.
</P>
<P>
He also said there is still untapped potentials for the two
countries to further promote their coopearation in the economic
and trade area. In 1998, bilateral trade amounted to 175 million
U.S. dollars, up by 15.3 percent over the previous year.
</P>
<P>
China is the largest developing nation in the world, while
Syria is an important country in the Middle East. So, it is in the
fundamental interests of the two peoples to strengthen and further
develop the Sino-Syrian cooperation, Li said.
</P>
<P>
It would also be conducive to strengthen the unity and
cooperation among the developing countries around the world, he
added.
</P>
<P>
China is willing to bring the momentum of further developing
bilateral cooperation into the 21st century on the basis of mutual
respect, equality and mutual benefit, Li said.
</P>
<P>
He also stressed that China has always been supporting the
just cause and demands of the Arab nations, including Syria, the
Middle East peace process, and all the efforts by the
international community to push forward the Middle East peace
process.
</P>
<P>
Zouebi warmly welcomed Li, who, he said, is an old friend from
a friendly country. The Prime Minister also expressed his
gratitude for China's all-along support to the Syrian and all the
Arab peoples in their cause for peace in the Middle East.
</P>
<P>
He said Syria would also like to see China play a bigger role
in the world affairs.
</P>
<P>
On the country's economic development, Zouebi said Syria is
now undertaking the policy of opening up in the area of economic
and trade development and welcome foreign businessmen to invest in
Syria.
</P>
<P>
Chinese enterprises who would like to invest in Syria are
especially welcomed, he said, promising that the government would
provide business-friendly conditions for the investors.
</P>
<P>
Syria is the third leg of Li's six-nation tour across Europe
and Asia, which has already taken him to Greece and Turkey, and
will further bring him to Pakistan, Bangladesh, and Thailand.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
