<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Singaporeans' Life Expectancy Increases </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SINGAPORE, April 7 (Xinhua) -- Singapore Health Minister Yeo
Cheow Tong said Wednesday that the average Singaporean's life
expectancy at birth is 77 years and the government is making
efforts to help people lead independent and meaningful lives
through a combination of individual efforts and community action.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a rally to mark the World Health Day, which falls
on April 7, Minister for Health and Minister for the Environment
Yeo said "for a man who has already reached the age of 60, he can
expect to survive for nearly 20 more years, and for a woman
another 22 years."
</P>
<P>
"My ministry's national health campaigns encourage people of
all ages to avoid smoking, eat a balanced diet, exercise regularly
and maintain a healthy weight," he said. "Observing these habits
will reduce the risk of heart disease, cancer and stroke and help
Singaporeans enter their golden years in good health."
</P>
<P>
Quoting the national health survey made in 1998, Yeo said that
the proportion of adults who smoked regularly declined from 18
percent in 1992 to 15 percent in 1998, while the proportion of
adults with high blood pressure rose from 22 percent to 27
percent.
</P>
<P>
The survey also showed that the prevalence of obesity and
diabetes remained unchanged, at 6 percent and 9 percent
respectively, he said.
</P>
<P>
"These results show that our health promotion activities had
some impact with regard to smoking and exercise. However, it was
not adequate to change dietary practices, especially with
increased affluence of the population," he said.
</P>
<P>
Referring to the fact that the World Health Organization (WHO)
has chosen for World Health Day 1999 the theme "Active Aging Makes
The Difference", Yeo said the principle of active aging is to
encourage people of all ages to take steps to ensure greater
health and well being in their later years for themselves and
their communities.
</P>
<P>
"WHO's message is particularly relevant to Singapore as we are
one of the fastest aging countries in the world," he added.
</P>
