<DOCNO> XIE19990407.0141 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S. Africa to Overhaul Immigration System </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
At the heart of the proposed policy is a reliance on market
forces to determine which skills are needed in South Africa. The
current system is based on maximum government control over
foreigners, the Business Day newspaper reported Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
A product of a specialist task team's year of study, it
recommends scrapping the discredited Immigration Selection Board
in favor of " objective criteria" administered by a regulatory
agency to be known as the Immigration Service.
</P>
<P>
This is intended to enable businesses to recruit foreign
workers on condition that they pay predetermined sums into a skill
training fund for South African workers.
</P>
<P>
Linked to this is a proposal for the government not to
interfere in determining how many foreigners, or what skills, are
needed in the labor market. Market forces will determine that.
</P>
<P>
The new immigration scheme will lead to a radical reduction in
the number of illegal immigrants found in workplaces. It is
estimated that there are five million illegal immigrants in South
Africa.
</P>
<P>
The Immigration Service will be empowered to negotiate
corporate visas, which are to be given to domestic companies for a
specified number of foreign workers on the basis of skill needs
and administered by the companies themselves.
</P>
<P>
Visitors from countries specified in the regulations will not
be required to obtain visas beforehand if they provide proof at
the port of entry of a return air ticket or other prescribed
guarantees.
</P>
<P>
Those entering across South Africa's land borders must possess
visas or travel documents issued by a South African diplomatic
mission. Alternatively, at all points of entry, people may enter
on the basis of a credit card procedure. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990407.0142 </DOCNO>
