<TEXT>
<P>
SINGAPORE, April 7 (Xinhua)-- Share prices remained bullish on
Singapore Stock Market Wednesday as heavy trading fueled momentum
for a third day.
</P>
<P>
The benchmark Straits Times Index gained 16.17 points to
1,622.32 points, hitting a 17-month new high after piecing the key
1,600-point level Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The volume totaled 568.19 million units worth 768.42 million
Singapore dollars (442.61 million U.S. dollars). Losers edged out
gainers by 175 to 127 with 129 counters unchanged.
</P>
<P>
Singatr topped the actives list of the day with a turnover of
39.25 million shares. It was followed by OCBC DBC w02 which had
21.93 million stocks done. JC MPH was the next with 21.30 million
counters changing hands.
</P>
<P>
DBS F and Venture w99 headed the ascent of the day, surging up
by 50 cents to close at 14.90 and 7.20 Singapore dollars
respectively. F&AMP;N and SIA gained 35 cents to finish at 6.95 and
9.15 Singapore dollars separately. SIA F , SPH and SPH F climbed
up 30 cents to end at 13.30, 20.50 and 20.50 Singapore dollars
respectively.
</P>
<P>
Bukit Sem and UOB F led losers of the day, falling by 30 cents
to close at 10.60 and 11.90 Singapore dollars respectively.
Creative 50 and GE Life sank 20 cents to finish at 20.10 and 1.90
Singapore dollars respectively. HL Fin moved down 17 cents to end
at 2.40 Singapore dollars.
</P>
<P>
Dealers attributed Wednesday's rally to continued ascent of
select shares which were spurred by good fund response to
newly-listed bank warrants.
</P>
<P>
They said that as foreign investors remain bullish, liquidity
continued to pour into the market for the third consecutive day.
</P>
<P>
They also noted there was note of caution that resistance will
start to build as the level of 1,600 points is twice the September
1998 low of 800. 
