<HEADLINE> Nigerian Locals Threaten to Take Over Oil </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
At the expiration of the ultimatum issued to the management of
Mobil Producing Nigeria Unlimited, the Ijaws Tuesday actualized
their threat to make oil operations difficult for all oil
companies operating in the region.
</P>
<P>
The newspapers said that the communities Tuesday seized five
barges, four tug boats and one sea truck belong to some of oil
companies in Delta State.
</P>
<P>
The communities are allegedly impacted by the January 12, 1998
Idoho platform oil spillage and are demanding a two billion naira
(about 22 million U.S. dollars) compensation from the American oil
firm.
</P>
<P>
Addressing newsmen Tuesday in Warri, capital of Delta State,
the coordinating secretary of the Association of Mobil Spill
Affected Communities, Ijawkeme Adam, said that the seizure of the
barges and tug boats was tip of the ice-berg as it was just the
first stage of their planned action in the area.
</P>
<P>
He noted that if the management of Mobil still remains adamant
to their plight, they would have no option than to take over all
the oil installations in the area.
</P>
<P>
The coordinating secretary pointed out that the communities
resorted to the militant approach because some officials of Mobil
were frustrating all attempts to dialog over the matter. 
</P>
