<HEADLINE> Hong Kong Stocks Close Nearly 5 Percent Higher </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, April 7 (Xinhua) -- Hong Kong share prices surged 4.
89 percent Wednesday, the first trading day after the Easter and
Qingming Festival holidays, to reach the highest level for more
than a year.
</P>
<P>
The stocks registered big increases across the board with the
Hang Seng Index surging 541.89 points to close at 11,614.87, its
highest level since March 24, 1998, when the index stood at 11,594.
33.
</P>
<P>
The big increase was propelled by good performances in Wall
Street, London and Tokyo during the long holiday break in Hong
Kong, brokers said.
</P>
<P>
Dealers said that the market sentiment was also helped by
expectations of a Sino-U.S. accord on China's entry into the World
Trade Organization during Chinese Premier Zhu Rongji's visit to
the United States.
</P>
<P>
Wednesday's turnover amounted to 7.903 billion HK dollars (1.
013 billion U.S. dollars), 4.608 billion HK dollars (590.77
million U.S. dollars) more than that of the previous session.
</P>
<P>
Banking shares rose 927.78 points, or 5.44 percent, to close at
17,970.59, while utilities, properties and commerce and industry
gained 3.15 percent, 5.41 percent and 5.34 percent respectively.
</P>
<P>
The red-chip Hang Seng China-Affiliated Corporations Index went
up 32.03 points, or 3.95 percent, to 843.48, while the H-share
index rose 18.74 points, or 5.20 percent, to 378.93.
</P>
<P>
The market opened strongly Wednesday with the key Hang Seng
Index gaining 426.71 points, or 3.85 percent, by the end of the
morning session. 
</P>
</TEXT>
