<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Weapon Cleaning up Operation Begins in Cambodia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PHNOM PENH, April 7 (Xinhua) -- The Cambodian government
started a weapon clean-up operation Wednesday, aiming at reducing
crimes and kidnappings and ensuring social security during the
Khmer New Year.
</P>
<P>
Nationwide disarmament is expected to last for three months. A
special mixed commission headed by Phnom Penh First Deputy
Governor Chea Sophara has been set up to crack down on people
carrying weapons and ammunition.
</P>
<P>
During the operation, Police and Military Police will be
deployed at Phnom Penh's main streets and some entrances to the
city to search for weapons.
</P>
<P>
The Cambodian government Friday took some tough measures to
improve the country's public security, such as cleaning up the
city's weapons, canceling all existing gun licenses, closing
shooting ranges, banning security officials from carrying weapons
when off-duty, and stopping unregulated sale of uniforms.
</P>
<P>
An official of the Ministry of Interior said that the rifles
held by companies, hotels, night clubs and restaurants are now
illegal.
If Private companies want to use security guards with long guns,
they can hire the police to do so.
</P>
<P>
According to Royal Cambodia Armed Forces (RCAF) General Meas
Sophea, legally licensed guns will be deemed illegal and
confiscated after their present licenses expire.
</P>
<P>
A partial survey of the city revealed that 10,130 guns were
held by residents, only 2,482 of which were legally owned.
</P>
<P>
Public order was still very poor in Cambodia in recent months.
Robberies, kidnapping, murders and other serious crimes were
rampant which not only severely affected people's normal life, but
also hindered foreign investment and the development of tourism.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
