<DOCNO> XIE19990407.0150 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Thailand Urges Balanced Growth for Mekong Subregion </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, April 7 (Xinhua) -- Thai Foreign Minister Surin
Pitsuwan opened a major development meeting here on Wednesday
calling for balanced growth in politics, social welfare and the
environment other than a singled-minded pursuit of unsubstainable
economic growth.
</P>
<P>
Delivering a keynote address at the Symposium on the
Comprehensive Development of the Greater Mekong Subregion, Surin
said that if the countries in the region followed the examples of
Thailand, Malaysia and Indonesia, where economic policy was
pursued to the exclusion of everything else, they will have
problems ahead.
</P>
<P>
"Social and human resources development must keep pace with
economic progress to make development sustainable," Surin noted.
</P>
<P>
He pinpointed single-minded pursuit of unsubstainable growth as
a major cause of the current economic turmoil in Asia, warning
that Mekong region governments must invest heavily in their people
or risk future crises.
</P>
<P>
The foreign minister blamed the economic crisis in Asia on the
fact that many of the countries affected lacked adequate human
resources and were extremely dependent on external funds,
technology and markets for their economic growth.
</P>
<P>
Other areas where progress needs to be made in the Greater
Mekong Subregion countries include improvement of infrastructure,
revision of rules governing cross-border trade, better human
resources development and greater involvement of the private
sector in economic development.
</P>
<P>
The two-day symposium, being held at the United Nations
Conference Center in Bangkok, is organized by the U.N. Economic
and Social Commission for Asia and the Pacific in cooperation with
the Asian Development Bank and the governments of Thailand and
Japan.
</P>
<P>
The Greater Mekong Subregion includes Thailand, Myanmar, Laos,
Cambodia and Vietnam. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
