<HEADLINE> WFP Announces Emergency Food Aid to 640,000 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ADDIS ABABA, April 7 (Xinhua) -- The World Food Program (WFP)
announced on Wednesday that it will provide emergency food aid to
640,000 drought- stricken pastoralists in the Somali region of
Ethiopia.
</P>
<P>
Rebecca Hansen, head of the relief unit of WFP Ethiopia, told
press here that pastoralists in the Somali region have been
migrating in search of water for themselves and their animals.
</P>
<P>
He noted that grazing conditions are much worse then normal for
this time of year and drinking water is in short supply, adding a
lack of rainfall during the two previous rainy seasons has only
exacerbated the drought conditions.
</P>
<P>
According to WFP Ethiopia, WFP has reallocated a total of 8,000
tons of food from Addis Ababa, Dire Dawa and Jijiga for the relief
effort and the Ethiopian government's relief institution is moving
the food locally to distribute sites throughout the Somali region.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, other United Nations' agencies and non-governmental
organizations are helping supply water in the Somali region.
</P>
<P>
"The overall situation is aggravated by a livestock ban from
the region to the Gulf states," Hansen said, adding that "Saudi
Arabia banned livestock imports from Somalia, Sudan, Ethiopia,
Eritrea, Djibouti and Kenya in February 1998 because of fears
that an outbreak of Rift Valley Fever could spread."
</P>
<P>
He said, "livestock prices have decreased significantly while
grain prices are increasing." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
