<HEADLINE> Chinese Premier Has Busy Day in Los Angeles </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LOS ANGELES, April 6 (Xinhua) -- Chinese Premier Zhu Rongji,
who arrived here Tuesday morning, met local leaders and public
figures before and after a luncheon hosted in his honor by Los
Angeles mayor Richard Riordan.
</P>
<P>
Among some 300 guests present were Los Angeles County Chairman
of the Board of Supervisors Don Knabe, U.S. ambassador to China
James Saser, former U.S. Secretary of State Warren Christopher,
congressmen and business leaders.
</P>
<P>
Welcoming the Chinese premier, Riordan said it is an honor for
Los Angeles to be chosen as the first stop of Zhu's official visit
to the United States.
</P>
<P>
Greater Los Angeles, he said, is an area in the United States
with the largest Chinese population and very close ties with China.
He hoped that these ties will grow extensively in the next century
and exchanges and cooperation between the United States and China
further expand.
</P>
<P>
In response, Premier Zhu said California and Los Angeles have
been playing an important role in Sino-U.S. trade and economic
relations.
</P>
<P>
He expected the mutually beneficial cooperation and friendly
exchanges between China and Los Angeles and California to
constantly develop, in pace with further improvements of the
relations between China and the United States.
</P>
<P>
Before the luncheon, Zhu met separately with Riordan, Knabe and
Governor of California Gray Davis at Century Plaza Hotel, where he
is staying.
</P>
<P>
Telling the guest that he will soon visit China as head of a
delegation, Davis expressed the hope that relations between China
and the United States would improve.
</P>
<P>
Other guests Zhu met with also shared the view that contacts
and exchange of visits at high levels are all the more necessary
when difficulties arise in bilateral relations. They said they
were especially glad that Premier Zhu will talk with President
Bill Clinton during his visit.
</P>
<P>
In the evening, Zhu attended a grand banquet in his honor
hosted by the Chinese community of Southern California.
</P>
<P>
Speaking to nearly 1,000 people at the banquet, a
representative of the host organizations described Zhu's visit as
a great event in Sino-U.S. relations, following the exchange of
visits by the heads of state of both countries.
</P>
<P>
Addressing the audience, Zhu said the purpose of his visit is
to further implement the mutual understanding reached by the heads
of state of the two countries during their exchange of visits and
to overcome obstruction and promote bilateral ties.
</P>
<P>
With mutual efforts of both sides and support of the two
peoples, this aim can surely be reached, he said.
</P>
<P>
Zhu briefed the audience about the latest developments of
China's economy and reform.
</P>
<P>
Earlier in the afternoon, Zhu met representatives from Chinese
companies operating in Los Angeles, Chinese students studying in
California and staff members at the Chinese consulate general in
Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
Zhu's wife Lao An, State Councilor Wu Yi, State Councilor and
Secretary-General of the State Council Wang Zhongyu and Zhu's
other entourage also attended the events on Tuesday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
