<HEADLINE> All Telephones in Dhaka to Be Digital Next Year </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, April 7 (Xinhua) -- All telephones in the Bangladeshi
capital of Dhaka and its adjoining areas will become digital by
June 2000 after the greater Dhaka telephone system development
project is implemented.
</P>
<P>
Under the project, about 40 percent of which has been
completed, 67,500 new digital lines will be installed by June
2000, according to a high-level meeting at the prime minister's
office on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The meeting was held to review the progress and implementation
of the greater Dhaka telephone system, and installation and
expansion of digital telephone exchange in different district
headquarters.
</P>
<P>
Some 71,000 new lines would also be installed under an extended
program of the project. By the year 2001, 442,250 new telephone
lines would be established in the public sector across the
country, and 300,000 lines would be installed in Dhaka under the
private sector.
</P>
<P>
There would be an estimated demand for 1.3 million telephones
in the country by the year 2002 against the 500,000 existing
lines, 223,000 of which are in the capital city.
</P>
<P>
Prime Minister Sheikh Hasina asked officials to expedite the
on-going projects so that 64 district headquarters of the country,
with a 126-million population, could be brought under digital
telephone networks.
</P>
<P>
Seventeen districts have been brought under a digital network
so far, Telecommunications Minister Mohammad Nasim said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
