<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Feature: A Cornered Tiger Who Still Fights (3) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Guobao's task was to paint artwork on the outside of an empty
eggshell, a very popular handicraft then. And when a Japanese
customer asked for a painted egg featuring a Buddha plus a
Buddhist scripture with 240 Chinese characters, few of Guobao's
factory colleagues dared to accept such a daunting job.
</P>
<P>
But he accepted without a second thought and worked out a
special technical way of ensuring that the characters would be
even and equal in size on such a small item. Thanks to his
developing this particular painting skill he was able to turn out
a dozen painted eggs a day.
</P>
<P>
And while an ordinary egg earned him 0.18 yuan each, his
scripture eggs earned four times as much each, a huge sum in those
days.
</P>
<P>
So for 13 years, Guobao, working from his bed and on his
stomach, happily painted eggs for the factory, and as a result of
hard-working spirit and considerable talent, was cited as a model
worker. His deeds were publicized by local newspapers, television
and radio.
</P>
<P>
Instead of becoming a burden, as he had feared, Guobao became
the financial pillar of the family. Apart from himself, he was
able to support his housewife mother and also paid for the
schooling of his younger brother and three sisters.
</P>
<P>
In 1985, as the demand for painted eggs declined, undeterred
Guobao changed to name-card printing, then a lucrative business.
Out of his savings he bought a special machine and launched the
Mingyuan Name-card Printing House. He even learned simple English
so that he could handle bilingual cards and adopted a new motto:
Flexibility, Perfection and Credibility. His business flourished.
He had to employ several hands in busy times to cope with
increasing orders.
</P>
<P>
Now, in the time of difficulty, he is still grateful to his
family for sticking by him and encouraging him. He still lives
with his now 76-year-old mother and the family of his married
brother, while his three devoted sisters often visit to help him,
with their husbands, when he is too ill to work.
</P>
<P>
And Guobao is loud in praise of his assistant and housemaid Xie
Qixiang who has worked for him since 1992. The 28 year-old from
Sichuan Province has proved to be a dedicated supporter and never
complains herself even when her monthly salary of 400 yuan is
delayed because Guobao can't afford it.
</P>
<P>
Such encouragement has made Guobao determined to make his
business boom again. "I'm determined never to become a burden to
anyone. I'm sure once I'm able to acquire modern equipment my
skills and hard work will see the business take off," said Guobao
confidently. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990407.0166 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> One Million U.S. Dollars Worth of Pearls Stolen in HK </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, April 7 (Xinhua) -- Hong Kong Police are
investigating a burglary Wednesday morning in which 7.6 million
Hong Kong dollars (nearly 1 million U.S. dollars) worth of pearls
were stolen from a jewelry shop in Central, Hong Kong's major
commercial district.
</P>
<P>
A press release issued by the police Wednesday said that
shortly after 9:15 a.m., the woman manager of the shop returned to
the premises and found that some pearls inside the shop were
missing upon opening the safe and some others in the showcase were
also missing.
</P>
<P>
Police said that no signs of ransacking were detected inside
the shop or were there any sings of a break-in. Investigations are
proceeding. 
</P>
</TEXT>
