<DOCNO> XIE19990407.0167 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Aussie Economy Likely to Exceed 3.25 Pct Growth  Forecast: Bank </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, April 7 (Xinhua) -- The Australian economy was likely
to exceed the Australian federal government's growth forecast of
3.25 percent in the current financial year but a period of slower
growth is at hand, the Commonwealth Bank of Australia Ltd (CBA)
said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
However, CBA strategist Michael Blythe said that at the moment
"any significant slowing in overall activity looks unlikely before
mid year."
</P>
<P>
According to economic outlook published by CBA, one of the four
biggest banks in the country, economic growth in the current
financial year ending on June 30, 1999, would reach around 4.0
percent and step down to 2.75 percent in the upcoming financial
year.
</P>
<P>
The latest national accounts showed growth running at a 4.7-
percent pace over 1998.
</P>
<P>
Despite the Asian economic crisis, the Australian economy has
been performing quite well over the past year as one of the
fastest growing economies in the industrialized world as a result
of robust domestic demand and diversification of its export
markets other than Asia.
</P>
<P>
"But there is also now some clear evidence to support our
contention that a period of slower growth is at hand," Blythe
said.
</P>
<P>
He said one pointer to slower growth was the gap opening up
between production and income in the economy as a whole.
</P>
<P>
The drop in Australia's terms of trade caused by a rise in
import prices represented a significant reduction in the
purchasing power of households and businesses.
</P>
<P>
"So while output may have risen by 4.7 percent during 1998, the
purchasing power of the income generated by that production - or
gross domestic income - rose by only 3.6 percent," Blythe said.
</P>
<P>
"Slower income growth is typically ultimately reflected in
lower spending levels.
</P>
<P>
Blythe noted the success Australian exporters achieved by
diverting to markets other than Asia over the past year but said
the feat would be difficult to repeat over next year.
</P>
<P>
"The pace of economic activity in Europe has slowed and some
step down in the U.S. growth rate from its current rapid pace is
also likely," he said.
</P>
<P>
"There are already some signs that exports to the U.S. and
Europe are weakening," he added.
</P>
<P>
On the upside, however, were positive signs emanating from some
Asian economies.
</P>
<P>
"At the very least, the rate of deterioration in these
economies is likely to slow this year," he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
