<DOCNO> XIE19990407.0170 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Estrada: Reprieve to Convicts Aims to Ensure Justice </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, April 7 (Xinhua) -- Philippine President Joseph Estrada
said Wednesday the 90-day reprieve he has granted to three death
row convicts would give him time to review their plea for
executive clemency and ensure justice.
</P>
<P>
Estrada said he needs time to look into the various aspects of
the case that may provide the grounds to commute the death
sentences of Dante Piandong, Jesus Morallos, and Archie Bulan.
</P>
<P>
"I am studying the case thoroughly so we can give justice to
all concerned, including the victim's family," he said in a radio
interview.
</P>
<P>
Estrada Tuesday granted a 90-day reprieve to the three men
convicted of killing a police officer in a robbery four years ago.
</P>
<P>
He announced the delay on the eve of the scheduled executions,
which would be the second in the Philippines in 23 years.
</P>
<P>
During the interview, Estrada also said he would not hesitate
to send convicted rapists and drug pushers to the lethal injection
chamber.
</P>
<P>
He said the 90-day reprieve he granted to the three robbers is
not a precedent that will be followed for other death row
convicts, stressing that this move is not a sign that his
administration has softened its stand towards criminals.
</P>
<P>
"The criminals I am really mad at are rapists and drug
pushers," he said. "These kinds of criminals deserve no mercy,
especially drug pushers who destroy the future of our youth," he
added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990407.0171 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zambia's Economy Expected to Grow in 1999 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, April 7 (Xinhua) -- The macro economic strategy adopted
by Zambian government in this year's budget is expected to yield
positive results especially with the restoration of balance of
payment support (BOP), Zambian local newspapers reported
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The reports quoted Barclays Bank of Zambia acting managing
director Andy Fair as saying in Lusaka Tuesday that the continued
inflow of International Monetary Fund (IMF) and other financiers
for BOP will act as strong boosters to stabilize macro economic
indicators.
</P>
<P>
While launching the Barclays Budget Digest 1999, Fair said the
economy was likely to stabilize with a more stable exchange rate
which would lead to a drop in inflation.
</P>
<P>
Fair said the reduction of inflation and interest rates were
critical to the prospect of economic growth during 1999.
</P>
<P>
The Digest indicates that the expected positive movements in
the regional and world economic environments might also play a
major part in hoisting Zambia's economy.
</P>
<P>
He said the reduction of inflation to a single-digit level by
the end of medium term strategy 1999 to 2001 and the strengthening
of the country's external financial position were achievable as
long as global economic environment continued to impact positively
on the Zambia's economy.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990407.0172 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> EU Invites Tanzania to Meet Over Fish Imports Ban </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, April 7 (Xinhua) -- The European Union (EU) has
invited Tanzania to a meeting in Brussels next week to review a
fish trade ban imposed in late March.
</P>
<P>
An official with the Tanzanian Ministry of Natural Resources
and Tourism, and Chairman of the Lake Victoria Fish Processors
Association, Harko Bhagat, among others, will attend the meeting,
a local newspaper said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
"The meeting will find out the best measures to address the
problem," the First Secretary of the EU delegation in Tanzania,
Ranieri Sabatuchi, told The Guardian here Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
On March 30, EU announced a total ban on fresh and frozen fish
imports from Tanzania, Kenya and Uganda, following reports that
Uganda and Kenya recently restricted the sales of poisoned fish
from Lake Victoria.
</P>
<P>
Unscrupulous fishermen in the world's second largest freshwater
lake, which borders the three east African countries, have long
been blamed for using insecticides or explosives, to catch Nile
Perch and other fish, posing threats to health.
</P>
<P>
Tanzania's Minister of Natural Resources and Tourism, Zakia
Meghji, however, has said pollution of fish products in the lake
area on her country's side has been controlled after the defense
force, the police and her ministry launched a joint operation
against the illegal fishing practices.
</P>
<P>
"Tanzania is confident that its fish is fit for human
consumption. We are ready for further tests by the European
Union," she said.
</P>
<P>
This is a second time for the EU to impose a ban on fish
imports from east African countries in the past two years.
</P>
<P>
In January last year, the EU froze imports of fresh fish
fillets from the three countries following an outbreak of cholera
in east Africa. The ban, which caused the three countries millions
of U.S. dollars of loss in exports, were not lifted until six
months later.
</P>
<P>
Tanzania earns some 85.6 million U.S. dollars from the fish
industry along the lake, providing 4,000 jobs.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990407.0173 </DOCNO>
