<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zimbabwe To Sell Ivory for First Time In 8 Years </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, April 7 (Xinhua) -- Zimbabwe will for the first time
sell its experimental 20-ton quota of raw elephant tusks to Japan
next Tuesday following the lifting of the eight-year ban on ivory
trade in June 1997, the daily Herald reported Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The ban was lifted at the 10th Convention of the Parties to the
 Convention on International Trade in Endangered Species (CITES)
which was held in Harare in June, 1997.
</P>
<P>
The experimental trade will also take place in Botswana, which
will sell about 25.3 tons and Namibia which will dispose of its
13.8-ton stockpile Friday. The move will help the three southern
African countries generate more revenue for elephant conservation,
and improve the lives of people living alongside elephants.
</P>
<P>
Briefing reporters in Harare Tuesday, Zimbabwe's Minister of
Mines, Environment and Tourism Simon Moyo said as part of the
CITES conditions for the resumption of the sale of ivory, Zimbabwe
declared 33.4 tons of raw ivory.
</P>
<P>
Of that total, 20 tons were to be sold to Japan, 8.8 tons were
for the donor buy-out declaration, while 4.6 tons were for local
sales.
</P>
<P>
He said Zimbabwe had met all the stringent conditions set by
CITES as recorded by its verification team at the 41st Standing
Committee Meeting of February this year.
</P>
<P>
He said the decision by the CITES to transfer the African
elephant from Appendix one to Appendix two, which allows for
restricted trade in elephant products, ushered in a new chapter in
the sustainable use and development of wildlife resources.
</P>
<P>
The country has an elephant population of about 70,000, almost
double its carrying capacity. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
