<HEADLINE> Egypt Sends Relief Aid to Kosovo Refugees </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, April 7 (Xinhua) -- Egypt on Wednesday sent 34 tonnes of
relief aid to refugees fleeing the war-torn Yugoslav province of
Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
The relief aid, which was flown to the Albanian capital of
Tirana, included 5.4 tonnes of medicines, 1,500 boxes of milk
powder, 500 boxes of canned foodstuffs and 1,000 blankets, Egypt's
Middle East News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
The aid was sent to Kosovars under an instruction of Egyptian
President Hosni Mubarak as a contribution of the Egyptian
government.
</P>
<P>
Hundreds of thousands of Kosovars have poured into Albania and
Mecedonia after the North Atlantic Treaty Organization launched
missile and air strikes against Yugoslavia on March 24.
</P>
<P>
NATO's attacks are aimed at forcing Yugoslav President Slobodan
Milosevic to sign a peace agreement, which requires Belgrade to
grant autonomy to the ethnic Albanians in Kosovo and allow NATO to
deploy peacekeeping forces there. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
