<HEADLINE> Australian Stocks Close Lower </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, April 7 (Xinhua) -- A strong performance from media
baron Rupert Murdoch's News Corp Ltd failed to inspire gains in
the rest of the sharemarket Wednesday as it closed marginally
lower.
</P>
<P>
The all ordinaries index softened 3.3 points to 3,029.6 with
most leaders, apart from News Corp, surrendering the gains of
Tuesday that took the market to a record close.
</P>
<P>
The all industrials index lifted 8.1 points to 5,463.7 while
all resources index dropped a hefty 17.7 points, 1.7 percent, to
1,034.2.
</P>
<P>
Overall volume figures showed turnover of 347.13 million shares
worth 744.1 million U.S. dollars with 652 stocks falling, 489
rising and 426 remaining steady.
</P>
<P>
Market leader News Corp rose 45 cents by the close to 13.53
Australian dollars on turnover of 8.03 million shares as it
continued to benefit from Tuesday's 2.1-billion-U.S.-dollar cable
television deal with U.S.-based Liberty Media.
</P>
<P>
News Corp's preferred scrip jumped 28.5 cents to 12.785
Australian dollars.
</P>
<P>
Bank stocks were lower with the industry sub-index sliding 38.5
points to 7,226.9 with ANZ bank a biggest loser.
</P>
<P>
ANZ retreated 26.5 cents to 11.295 Australian dollars,
Commonwealth Bank of Australia off-loaded three cents to 26.89
Australian dollars, Westpac bank shed 12.5 cents to 11.613
Australian dollars and National Australia Bank dropped five cents
to 28.75 Australian dollars.
</P>
<P>
Resource stocks were led lower by diversified miner BHP, which
dropped 33.4 cents to 13.61 Australian dollars on profit taking.
</P>
<P>
In the other majors, global miner Rio Tinto slipped 17 cents to
21.67 Australian dollars.
</P>
<P>
The gold index surrendered 25.8 points to 968.7 despite a
1.60-U.S.- dollar firming in bullion to 280.00 U.S. dollars an
ounce in Sydney in late trade. 
</P>
