<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-07 09:38 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iranian Revolutionary Court Closes Moderate Daily </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, April 7 (Xinhua) -- An Iranian revolutionary court on
Wednesday ordered the moderate Persian-language daily Zan (Women)
be closed until further notice.
</P>
<P>
Head of the Tehran revolutionary court Gholamhussein Rahbarpour
told the Islamic Republic News Agency (IRNA) that the paper was
banned for publishing a letter of Farah Diba, the ousted Iranian
queen, on April 3 and a caricature making fun of "blood money" on
April 6.
</P>
<P>
Rahbarpour said the mere publication of Farah's message
on the new Iranian year (March 21) was a "blatant anti-revolutionary
act" and publicity for the "vicious" (monarchical) regime, which
was overthrown in the 1979 Islamic revolution.
</P>
<P>
He also said publishing a caricature to ridicule blood money
-- money paid to the family of a murdered person as compensation
by the murderer, which is one of the main judicial and religious
principles of Islam, is considered as a direct insult.
</P>
<P>
IRNA said Faezeh Hashemi, managing director of the daily and
daughter of former Iranian President Hashemi Rafsanjani, has been
summoned twice in a week by the hard-line conservative
revolutionary court to give explanations on the issue.
</P>
<P>
Hashemi told the editorial staff of the newspaper on Tuesday
night that she assumes responsibility for publishing the paper and
the caricature and that she has reasons for publishing each of
them.
</P>
<P>
Late last year, the daily Zan was ordered to suspend publishing
for two weeks for violating relevant laws, but the daily rejected
the charges.
</P>
<P>
Faezeh Hashemi is a famous Iranian activist for women rights
and has close relations with the moderate party of Constructive
Executives of Iran headed by former Tehran mayor Gholamhussein
Karbaschi, who was sentenced to two-year imprisonment on graft
charges. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
