<DOCNO> XIE19990407.0186 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Zoo Puts Animals On Diet </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HEFEI, April 7 (Xinhua) -- A Chinese zoo has successfully
slimmed down a number of its obese animals by "persuading" them to
adopt a partially vegetarian diet.
</P>
<P>
In the past four months about a dozen tubby beasts, including
tigers, lions and leopards, in Hefei Zoo, in this capital of east
China's Anhui province, have been on a weight-watchers diet.
</P>
<P>
Although 80 percent of their food is meat, zookeepers
supplemented it with 20 percent of vegetables, which normally
carnivores won't eat.
</P>
<P>
"Obesity in captive animals is a problem facing zoos worldwide
because of the lack of exercise animals linked to a rich diet
mainly of meat," according Wu Zhi'an, head of Heifei's City Zoo's
general management section.
</P>
<P>
A real worry for zookeepers and anthropologists is that as a
result of this situation there are increasing numbers of animals
in captivity in declining health and there are also breeding
problems.
</P>
<P>
Hefei City Zoo has about 60 carnivorous animals, and now plans
to gradually introduce this diet for all of them. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
