<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Elderly Not Healthy Enough: Chinese Health Ministry </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 7 (Xinhua) -- Medical experts said that although
more and more Chinese are living longer, the elderly are now faced
with under-developed medical services which may greatly threaten
their health.
</P>
<P>
Life expectancy in China now averages 70 years, but only 32.7
percent of the elderly men and 38.5 percent of the aged women are
healthy, according to the latest statistics provided by the Health
Ministry at a symposium today marking the World Health Day.
</P>
<P>
According to these statistics, high blood pressure, coronary
heart disease, diabetes, stroke, cancer, dementia in the elderly,
and osteoporosis are the major threats to elderly Chinese.
</P>
<P>
At the same time, many old people suffer from blindness,
deafness and some movement-dysfunctional diseases. Other
statistics indicate that more than half of the disabled in China
are the elderly.
</P>
<P>
Health departments in all localities should go all out to
improve medical service and provide appropriate medical insurance
for old people, Vice Health Minister Wang Longde said.
</P>
<P>
China has the largest elderly population in the world, with 120
million people over 60 years of age, and nine million 80 years old
or more.
</P>
<P>
Experts predict that the number of elderly Chinese will reach
more than 400 million by the middle of the next century.
</P>
<P>
The World Health Organization has called for better health care
for the aging population, especially on this World Health Day
whose theme is "active aging."
</P>
<P>
The organization urges all of society and all families of the
world to care more about their elders.
</P>
<P>
Chinese health organizations plan to publicize health education
and opportunities for free medical services for the aging.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
