<DOCNO> XIE19990407.0192 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: Hedge Funds Expand Investments in Thailand </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, April 7 (Xinhua) -- Foreign hedge funds, encouraged by
signs of economic recovery in Thailand, are making a steady
comeback in the hope of good returns in the next three or four
years, business sources said.
</P>
<P>
Hedge funds are entering Thailand with their investment sizes
ranging from 700-800 million to 1 billion U.S. dollars, Suvarn
Valaisathien, an expert on business law, said.
</P>
<P>
He told a recent economic seminar that the funds are believed
to allocate about 50-60 million dollars for each acquisition.
</P>
<P>
Such foreign capital inflows are being witnessed for
investments both in the capital market and direct investment,
especially after the government announced a series of measures to
boost the embattled economy, according to Prasarn Trairatvorakul,
deputy secretary-general of the Securities and Exchange Commission
(SEC) in Thailand.
</P>
<P>
"I don't mind the movement," he said in response to a question
on what happens if the funds stay in the country for only three to
four years.
</P>
<P>
It has been a common practice by hedge funds to flood any
crisis-stricken country to take advantage of cheap assets but flee
after making gains.
</P>
<P>
A number of foreign investors have acquired stakes in local
companies. For instance, Holderbank of Switzerland has a majority
stake in Siam City Cement Plc while Jalaprathan Cement Plc
recently welcomed Cement Francais as a major shareholder.
</P>
<P>
Golden Land Property Development Plc also sold its new shares
to Quantum Fund of George Soros and Big C Supercenter Plc becomes
the latest local corporation to sell shares to Giant International
BV and Casino Guichard Pirrachor SA.
</P>
<P>
Many Thais regard foreign hedge funds as one of the factors
that led to the financial crisis as the funds try every means to
make profits at the sacrifices of others.
</P>
<P>
The sources attribute hedge funds' participation in Thailand to
cheap investment -- around 50 percent from peak prices in
1995-1997 -- with expected higher returns in the future. The
annual average returns is expected to stay at 30-40 percent. As
money-making funds, these investors will sell all stakes after
receiving attractive returns.
</P>
<P>
Vichai Punpocha, country manager of Dresdner Bank AG, said the
hedge funds, like other investors, could encounter investment
risks but it would be worth their while if the assets are
relatively cheap.
</P>
<P>
But it seems many hedge funds are nowadays speculating less on
foreign exchanges after they got their fingers badly burnt
following the crises in Russia and Brazil. They are allocating
more resources for longer-term investment purposes and Thailand is
one of the countries attracting such investment, market sources
said.
</P>
<P>
Many sectors in Thailand appeal to the funds. Hospitals are
very interesting to foreign investors, so are hotel and tourism
businesses, said the sources, who refused to be identified.
</P>
<P>
The types of investment could vary. Some are pure speculators
or venture capital companies, while others could hope to be
strategic partners.
</P>
<P>
These funds are seeking to gain stakes, via the rights issue
purchase, to acquire any company whose debt restructuring is now
under way and whose prospects are bright.
</P>
<P>
Corporate debt restructuring is expected to speed up
significantly thanks to the hedge funds' investment expansion,
some business sources maintained.
</P>
<P>
"But these funds are unlikely to take management control," one
source said.
</P>
<P>
Most of the hedge funds, which are under-regulated since their
major investment areas are overseas, are formed in the United
States where financiers are highly familiar with sophisticated
investment techniques. Many are managed by well-known financial
wizards such as Baton Biggs of Tiger Fund and George Soros of
Quantum Fund. Many financial companies, such as Goldman Saches and
Lehman Brothers, are also involved. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990407.0193 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> India's Fiscal Deficit In 1998-99 Up </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, April 7 (Xinhua) -- India's Fiscal deficit for the
just-ended financial year 1998-99 is likely to go up to 7 percent
of the gross domestic product (GDP), according to the latest
statistics released by the Finance Ministry.
</P>
<P>
While presenting the budget for 1999-2000 just five weeks ago,
Finance Minister Yashwant Sinha had estimated the government's
fiscal deficit for 1998-99 at 1,037.37 billion rupees
(approximately 24.7 billion U.S. dollars), or 6.5 percent of the
GDP.
</P>
<P>
Due to shortfall in revenue collection by over 50 billion
rupees (some 1.19 billion dollars) and capital receipts from the
disinvestment of the government's shares in the public sector
undertakings by around 30 billion rupees (714 million U.S.
dollars), the fiscal deficit from April 1, 1998, to March 31,
1999, is likely to touch 7 percent of the GDP.
</P>
<P>
Despite a substantial growth in the revenue collections last
month, the Finance Ministry said, it could not achieve its revised
estimate which had already scaled down to 1,443.28 billion rupees
(34.36 billion dollars) from the budget figure of 1,533.18 billion
rupees (36.5 billion dollars).
</P>
<P>
In its latest figures, the ministry estimated the total revenue
collection at 1,373.4 billion rupees (32.7 billion dollars), a
shortfall of around 70 billion rupees (1.66 billion dollars) to
meet the target.
</P>
<P>
However, a finance ministry spokesman said that this was only a
provisional figure and the ministry was confident of covering
another 20 billion rupees (476 million dollars). 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
