<DOCNO> XIE19990407.0198 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Hunan Province Fighting Harder Against Industrial Pollution </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CHANGSHA, April 7 (Xinhua) -- Central China's Hunan Province
plans to use 7.9 billion yuan to help its 2,300 manufacturers meet
the national pollution discharge standards ahead of a deadline set
for the year 2000.
</P>
<P>
The money will be spent in effectively treating various
industrial pollutants, according to the Provincial Environmental
Protection Bureau.
</P>
<P>
It disclosed that Hunan is home to 217 out of the country's 3,
000 heaviest industrial polluters. It has monitored the rising
index of 12 major pollutants that are under strict state
monitoring.
</P>
<P>
The bureau's recent investigations into pollution show that the
province discharges 1.3 billion tons of sewage, 345 billion cu.m.
of waste gas, 200 tons of cyanide and 180 tons of lead annually.
Because of the heavy pollution, two acid rain areas have appeared
in the valley of the Xiangjiang River, a river that irrigates 40
percent of the farmland in the province. 
</P>
</TEXT>
