<HEADLINE> Jordan Welcomes Suspension of U.N. Sanctions on </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
AMMAN, April 7 (Xinhua) -- The Jordanian government welcomed a
U.N. decision to lift sanctions on Libya following the hand-over
of two suspects of the 1988 Lockerbie bombing, Jordan Times
reported Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Jordanian Foreign Minister Abdul Ilah Khatib described the
hand-over as a positive step taken by Libya to cooperate with the
world community to solve the case of Lockerbie bombing, which
triggered sanctions by the United Nations on Libya in 1992, the
paper said.
</P>
<P>
The two Libyans were believed to be responsible for the bombing
of a Pan American airliner over Lockerbie, Scotland in 1988 which
killed 270 people. The United States and Britain had demanded that
Libya hand over the two for trial before a group of Scottish judges
in the Netherlands under Scottish laws.
</P>
<P>
Khatib said the Jordanian government was looking forward to
seeing a formal and complete ending of sanctions on Libya
following the hand-over of the two suspects. 
</P>
