<HEADLINE> Lebanon Condemns Israeli Expulsion of Civilians </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, April 7 (Xinhua) -- Lebanese President Emile Lahoud
has strongly condemned Israel's "barbaric" practices against
Lebanese civilians expelled by Israeli forces from their homes in
south Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
"Israel's systematic barbaric practices violate international
conventions and the most basic human rights on a daily basis," the
Daily Star Wednesday quoted Lahoud as saying.
</P>
<P>
The practices are also a flagrant violation of the 1996
agreement between the Jewish state and Lebanese guerrillas group
Hezbollah which stipulates no targeting of civilians in their
confrontations, he said.
</P>
<P>
The agreement was brokered by the United States in April, 1996
to end a 16-day Israeli blitz on Lebanon in which nearly 200
Lebanese, mostly civilians, were killed.
</P>
<P>
On Tuesday, Israeli forces expelled 25 Lebanese residents from
their village of Shebaa in the eastern sector of the Israeli
occupied border zone in south Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
The expulsion came in response to Monday's desertion by four
militiamen of the pro-Israeli South Lebanon Army (SLA).
</P>
<P>
Most of the deported are relatives of the four defectors who
reportedly sneaked out of Shebaa through the hills at dawn and
turned themselves in to the Lebanese army.
</P>
<P>
Also on Tuesday, Israeli forces arrested a number of SLA
officers from Haasbaya district, about 10 kilometers north of
Shebaa, and took them to the Israeli forces' south Lebanon command
in Marjayoun for interrogation over the desertion.
</P>
<P>
There are currently nearly 2,500 SLA members, who are helping
Israeli forces patrol its occupied border zone in south Lebanon
and handling the security affairs in Jezzine, a predominantly
Christian town facing the zone.
</P>
<P>
The militiamen were considered as traitors in Lebanon and its
commander Antonie Lahd has been sentenced to death in absentia by
a Lebanese military court.
</P>
<P>
Amid mounting speculation that Israeli forces may conduct a
unilateral partial withdrawal from south Lebanon, the SLA's morale
is sinking and more members are defecting to the Lebanese
government in a bid to escape a reprisals afterwards.
</P>
<P>
Israel set up a self-proclaimed security zone in south Lebanon
in 1985 with the claimed aim of protecting its north from Lebanese
guerrillas' cross-border attacks.
</P>
<P>
Since then, Lebanon's resistance movement spearheaded by the
Iranian-backed Hezbollah, or Party of God, has been fighting to
oust Israeli occupation forces and its ally SLA out of the
country. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
