<DOCNO> XIE19990407.0207 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Feature: A Cornered Tiger Who Still Fights (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 7 (Xinhua) -- For over three decades, paraplegic
Liu Guobao has been forced to lie flat on his stomach unable to
take even short steps or sit upright in a wheelchair.
</P>
<P>
Yet from his bed, from where he eats, sleeps and works, in his
simply furnished home, he has also been running for many years a
once booming printing business despite his handicap.
</P>
<P>
Because of his meticulous efforts and high standards, the
Mingyuan (meaning: bright prospect for tomorrow) Name-card
Printing House which he launched in 1985, has won him recognition
far and wide. Among his clients are senior-ranking government
officials, famous local artists, foreign diplomats and both
Chinese and foreign business people. On two occasions he was
selected as a model self-employed entrepreneur in Beijing's Xuanwu
District where he lives and works.
</P>
<P>
But now, after years of struggling to make a living rather than
be a burden on his family, more misfortune is piling on the
heavily-built shoulders of Guobao, as he battles to compete with
modern printing technology such as laser composing and offset
printing.
</P>
<P>
At 49 years of age Liu Guobao has found that his outdated
letterpress printing technique has been replaced by computer aided
equipment which he simply cannot afford.
</P>
<P>
According to him, orders have fallen sharply and his monthly
turnover has been reduced to a few hundred yuan from its heyday of
over 4,000 yuan (482 US dollars).
</P>
<P>
Even his old printing blocks need to be replaced but nobody
makes them anymore. He had saved hard to buy new equipment and
even gave up his 30-year-long smoking habit, one of his few
pleasures, but again disaster struck when in 1997 he caught
pyelitis and cystitis, as a result of his condition. He had to use
all his savings for medical treatment.
</P>
<P>
A fighter to the end Guobao has pleaded for bank loans but no
avail, since he has no collateral to back up his request.
</P>
<P>
However, Mr. Liu is determined to try and overcome these
problems and he is encouraged by a calligraphy artwork which hangs
on the wall of his home which features four bold and vigorous
Chinese characters which in English mean: "A Cornered Tiger Who
Still Fights."
</P>
<P>
It is actually dedicated to Liu Guobao personally, who was born
in the year of the Tiger in 1950, and presented to him by renowned
Beijing calligrapher Bo Tao in praise of his courageous struggle
for survival in the face of almost impossible odds.
</P>
<P>
This is now Guobao's motto although he admits, despite always
putting on a happy face, that he does feel uncertain about his
future unless he can find someone or some organization to help him
reestablish his business.
</P>
<P>
He never complains about his condition and has such a passion
for work that his friends and family are convinced he would have
become a hugely successful businessman if not for his disability.
</P>
<P>
His story really is one of tremendous courage in the face of
adversity, just as Bo Tao has indicated.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990407.0210 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kenyan Oil Firms Review Petroleum Prices </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, April 7 (Xinhua) -- The retail prices of petroleum
products in Kenya are set to go up following the price increase
announced by Abu Dhabi National Oil Corporation (Adnoc), the main
supplier of oil to the African country, according to local
industry sources here.
</P>
<P>
The sources said Adnoc had pegged March's crude oil price at
12. 75 U.S. dollars per barrel, an increase of nearly 25 percent
over February' s 10.25 dollars, the East African Standard
newspaper reported Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Executives of oil marketing firms in Nairobi said the retail
prices of petroleum products would be adjusted upward to a hike
of 2.5 dollars from the Adnoc oil supplier.
</P>
<P>
They said the oil firms had gone back to the drawing boards to
compute margins of pump price increment based on the hike of cost
for crude oil, Kenyan shilling and dollar exchange rate and cost
of transport among other factors.
</P>
<P>
The pump price increment is expected to trigger a wave of
inflationary pressure as the cost of transport constitutes a
large proportion of the final cost of oil products, the sources
noted.
</P>
<P>
To bolster crude prices to higher levels, members of the
Organization of

Petroleum Exporting Countries (OPEC) reduced production by 1.7
million barrels per day and 400,000 barrels for no members,
effective last Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Managing Director J. Segman of the Kenol/Kobil, a major oil
firm in Kenya, said last week a hike of one shilling to 1.5
shillings per liter is expected soon, and other firms said it was
inevitable due to international market trend.
</P>
<P>
The sources noted that the increased cost of crude oil will be
passed on to consumers, in order to ensure continued supply of oil
products. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
