<DOCNO> XIE19990407.0214 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Feature: A Cornered Tiger Who Still Fights (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Born into an ordinary worker's family in Beijing Liu Guobao is
the eldest of five children and as a young man was a bright
student full of ideals and ambitions. He dreamed of becoming a
soldier to defend his motherland or a sportsman determined to win
for his country.
</P>
<P>
But fate played its part when at only 15 years of age his young
dreams were shattered. On January 6, 1965 he was taking part in a
physical training class in Beijing's No 41 Middle School when he
suddenly felt a severe pain in his spine. He was diagnosed with
myelitis. In desperation his parents took him to a dozen hospitals
in the capital but was told by all the medical experts that he
would never stand upright again.
</P>
<P>
The news made Liu Guobao desperate and the though that he would
become a burden on his already financially strained family, and
the society in general, almost drove him to madness. Secretly he
began to collect sleeping pills, planning to commit suicide. But
as he reflected on his loving parents and family and how they
would be heart-broken at such an act, he soon abandoned this
notion.
</P>
<P>
At this time, China was pitched into the devastating "Cultural
Revolution" and even normal children were deprived of an education,
schools were closed down and books burnt.
</P>
<P>
This was when Guobao had his first stroke of luck when his
younger brother brought him dozens of famous Chinese and foreign
books which he had rescued from a burning pit in a nearby school.
The family could never have afforded to buy them in normal times
and they helped young Guobao become an avid reader. The books, he
says, gave him the courage to fight for his survival the best way
he could.
</P>
<P>
Then in 1968 his father, the family's only bread winner, died
of sudden illness. From that time on Guobao, as the eldest son,
vowed to learn enough skills to support the family. His
determination and will power impressed the famous Chinese figure
painter Zhao Shizhen and his colleague Aisin Giorro Shu Heng, the
well-known landscape painter, and they took on the then 23-year-
old Guobao as a student in May 1973.
</P>
<P>
By that time his physical condition had deteriorated and he
wasn't able to use a wheelchair. In order to learn how to paint he
had to first learn to lie flat on his stomach which was very
difficult and often made him feel sick. But he persevered and his
mother tucked in a large cushion to help relieve the stress on his
stomach.
</P>
<P>
For hours and hours Guobao practiced his painting skills, often
refusing meals. On one occasion while painting a difficult
traditional figure, at the request of his teachers, he carried on
for 24 hours without a break, which was another indication of his
determination to succeed.
</P>
<P>
His efforts paid off and on June 10, 1973, he was offered a
temporary job by a local arts and crafts factory and from that day
on gave up his government disability allowance. This, he declares,
was his second birthday.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990407.0215 </DOCNO>
