<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Tightening Urban Trash Controls </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 7 (Xinhua) -- China plans to increase the urban
garbage treatment capacity and to make an effort to hold the
amount of urban trash to 180 million tons by next year, according
to Zhu Guangyao, the deputy-director of the State Environmental
Protection Administration.
</P>
<P>
Daily urban garbage treatment capacity will be increased to 170,
000 tons, or 50 percent of the total. The treatment is expected to
be environmentally-friendly. Zhu told a recent symposium that the
amount of urban garbage in China has increased rapidly in the past
decade, but treatment has been hampered by a lack of funds,
mismanagement, and backward techniques.
</P>
<P>
Zhu has asked government departments to encourage enterprises
to develop treatment technology and facilities with preferential
policies and funds.
</P>
<P>
China had 666 cities in 1997. They produce 440 kilograms of
garbage per capita each year and random disposal methods have
caused large amounts of land to be wasted and have caused serious
air, river, lake, and ground water pollution problems.
</P>
<P>
Trash dumps on 500 million square meters of land currently
encircle more than 200 Chinese cities, according to an earlier
report by Science Times.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
