<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Churches Built by Germans to Reopen in Qingdao </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
QINGDAO, April 7 (Xinhua) -- A Protestant church and a Catholic
church, both built here by Germans early this century, are
scheduled to reopen to tourists here on May 1.
</P>
<P>
The churches, located downtown in the coastal city of Qingdao
in east China's Shandong Province, have been closed for repairs
since March 1.
</P>
<P>
The renovation project will cost some 4.19 million yuan, and
major repairs include interior decoration, replacement of a number
of statues, installation of new windows, as well as the
restoration of other facilities.
</P>
<P>
This is the second time repairs have been made on the churches
since 1949. The first was in 1980, before they were reopened after
being shut down for a dozen years.
</P>
<P>
Qingdao became an open port at the end of the last century when
a great many foreigners from the United States, Germany, Britain
and other countries came to live in the city, and the two churches
were specially built for them.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
