<DOCNO> XIE19990407.0222 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Experts Suggest Eggs and Milk Better for Breakfast </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 7 (Xinhua) -- Many Chinese schoolchildren are
suffering from malnutrition according to the results of a recent
survey which indicated they have an unbalanced diet.
</P>
<P>
Chinese nutritionists now believe that eggs and milk are the
better and more suitable food for everyday breakfast, Guangming
Daily reported today.
</P>
<P>
A nutritious breakfast provides sufficient energy and fulfils
parts of people's basic daily calorific needs, according to Liu
Liren, a nutritionist from east China's Jiangsu Province.
</P>
<P>
However, despite the improved living standards of Chinese
residents many neglect breakfast, which nutritionists says is the
most important meal of the day.
</P>
<P>
Calcium-rich milk and eggs are very easy to absorb, the
nutritionists believe.
</P>
<P>
City residents need only spend one yuan (12 U.S. cents) on a
bottle of milk and six yuan for a kilogram of eggs, the newspaper
said.
</P>
<P>
It seems that most Chinese people eat porridge every morning
and pickles, which lack calorie and nutritious elements, it said.
</P>
<P>
Statistics from the China milk industry association indicated
that each Chinese person drinks 6.6 kilograms of milk on average
every year, a very tiny amount compared to the world per capita of
102 kilograms.
</P>
<P>
Experts warned, however, that some people in inland provinces
favor alcohol much more than milk.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
