<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-07 07:11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cyprus Insists on Inviolability of Borders </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, April 7 (Xinhua) -- Cyprus' Foreign Minister Ioannis
Kasoulides said Tuesday night both Greece and Cyprus are concerned
over developments in Yugoslavia and underline the need to insist
on the inviolability of borders.
</P>
<P>
Speaking upon his return from Athens where he met his Greek
counterpart George Papandreou and Alternate Foreign Minister,
Yiannos Kranidiotis, Kasoulides said he is concerned over the
possibility of creating a precedent in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
According to the Cyprus News Agency (CNA), Kasoulides has
pointed out that neither the bombings nor the brutalities
carried out against the people of Yugoslavia, especially the
Albanians, will help the situation in the area.
</P>
<P>
He said a political and diplomatic solution should be reached
within the boundaries of Yugoslavia, just as any solution to the
Cyprus issue should be within the island's shores.
</P>
<P>
Kasoulides said Cyprus relies on the U.N. Charter,
U.N. resolutions and international law, "which are now under
trial in Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
The NATO air strikes against Yugoslavia, which started on March
24, are causing both military and civilian ccasualties. The
western alliance hoped the air strikes could force Yugoslav
President Slobodan Milosevic to agree to a peace deal with
separatist ethnic Albanians, who make up 90 percent of the
population in the Serbian province of Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile the Kosovo refugee crisis worsened as more ethnic
Albanians streamed into neighboring countries. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
