<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-07 07:27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Jordanian PM Denies Application for GCC membership </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
AMMAN, April 7 (Xinhua) -- Jordanian Prime Minister Abdul Raouf
Rawabdeh Tuesday night denied reports that his country has applied
to join the Gulf Cooperation Council (GCC) to strengthen ties
with the oil-rich Gulf region.
</P>
<P>
In a statement to Jordan TV, Rawabdeh said the issue was
neither discussed nor on the agenda during Jordanian King Abdullah
Bin Hussein's just-concluded three-day visit to Saudi Arabia.
</P>
<P>
The London-based newspaper Al Quds Al Arabi said in its Monday
edition that King Abdullah will officially inform Saudi officials
of Jordan's desire to join the GCC later this year.
</P>
<P>
The paper also quoted senior Arab sources as saying Saudi
Arabia has initially agreed to Jordan's request.
</P>
<P>
The GCC, which was founded in 1981 to boost regional
cooperation, now groups Saudi Arabia, Kuwait, Oman, Qatar, Bahrain
and the United Arab Emirates.
</P>
<P>
King Abdullah wrapped up his three-day visit to Saudi Arabia
Tuesday night, and Rawabdeh has termed the monarch's talks with
Saudi leaders as "highly successful."
</P>
<P>
Saudi Arabia was the largest donor to Jordan prior to the 1990
Gulf crisis triggered by Iraq's invasion of Kuwait, but Riyadh
suspended its annual economic aid of some 200 million dollars
after Jordan was found to be siding with Iraq during the crisis.
</P>
<P>
Abdullah's visit to Riyadh was part of his effort to rally
support in the Arab world for the stagnant economy of his desert
kingdom.
</P>
<P>
A busy diplomatic agenda in April will also take the Jordanian
ruler to Syria, Kuwait, the United Arab Emirates and other
countries to discuss bilateral ties and regional issues. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
