<HEADLINE> NATO Continues Bombing Civilian Targets in Yugoslavia: Report </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BELGRADE, April 7 (Xinhua) -- Yugoslavia's state-run Tanjug
news agency on Wednesday accused the North Atlantic Treaty
Organization of continuing to bomb civilian targets in several
cities, including Belgrade, Cacak, Lucani, Pancevo, Pristina and
Novi Sad, on the 15th day of air strikes.
</P>
<P>
Tanjug reported that at 2:40 am local time Wednesday (0045 GMT),
NATO missiles hit a fuel depot and a garage at an oil refinery
near Novi Sad and caused two powerful explosions. The only
remaining road-railway bridge across the Danube was also pounded.
Two other bridges over the river were destroyed in earlier
bombardments.
</P>
<P>
Serbia's RTS television station reported that apartment blocks
were hit in a NATO air raid in central Pristina early Wednesday,
killing and wounding several people.
</P>
<P>
On Tuesday night, three blasts rocked Belgrade. The Yugoslav
air and air defense forces launched counterattacks against the
NATO planes hovering over Belgrade.
</P>
<P>
A major chemical complex in the central Serbian town of Lucani
was hit by bombs.
</P>
<P>
Blasts reverberated in the air over the capital city of Kosovo,
Pristina, and its outskirts. NATO jet fighters bombed the Pristina
airport and an oil depot 10 kilometers northeast of the city.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
