<HEADLINE> EDS: Update with Political analysts hke040723 --  Sri Lanka's Ruling Party Wins All Five Provinces </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, April 7 (Xinhua) -- Sri Lanka's Ruling People's
Alliance (PA) Wednesday has won all five provincial councils
unexpectedly in the bitterly contested elections that were seen as
a test of popularity for the government and the president.
</P>
<P>
The Elections Commissioner announced that the PA scored victory
in Tuesday's voting in the provinces of Western, Central, North
Central, Uva and Sabaragamuwa, winning 46.25 percent votes or 120
seats plus 10 bonus seats out of 273 seats.
</P>
<P>
The results showed that the main opposition United National
Party (UNP) had given the PA a tough fight in most voting
districts.
</P>
<P>
The UNP got 43.48 percent votes or 112 seats.
</P>
<P>
The third largest party People's Liberation Front gained 5.46
percent votes or 15 seats.
</P>
<P>
Political analysts here had predicted the PA would won two or
three provinces but never expected an overall victory.
</P>
<P>
The surprise victory will probably encourage the government of
President Chandrika Kumaratunga to put forward presidential and
parliamentary elections due next year, they said.
</P>
<P>
Election officials said some 69 percent of the estimated 7.1
million voters had cast ballots.
</P>
<P>
At least two people was killed in poll-related violence on
Tuesday as the private Center for Monitoring Election Violence
reported several incidents of assaults, intimidation and electoral
malpractice towards the end of voting.
</P>
<P>
The government deployed 35,000 policemen to guard polling
booths and ensure security at counting centers where 60,000
officials were engaged in counting. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
