<HEADLINE> Poll Shows Worst of Asian Crisis Over </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, April 7 (Xinhua) -- Delegates to the on-going
Asia-Pacific Bankers Congress have voiced their optimism that the
worst of the worst of the two-year-old Asian financial crisis is
over.
</P>
<P>
A poll, conducted by DHL Worldwide Express, asked 250 delegates
to the congress which started here Tuesday about the outlook for
the region's economy.
</P>
<P>
About 77 percent of respondents believe that Asia has
experienced the worst of the economic crisis, while 65 percent
still believe that it will take one to two more years for the
economy to fully recover.
</P>
<P>
According to the poll, the majority of respondents believe that
Singapore is the best economic model for Asian countries, the
United States the second best and Japan the third.
</P>
<P>
When asked whether individual countries would emerge stronger
or weaker as the region recovers from the crisis, 57 percent
believe that Thailand would be stronger, while 40 percent said
that Malaysia would become weaker.
</P>
<P>
The three-day meeting is being dominated by discussions about
the financial reforms and solutions to the millennium bug threat
to the banking industry. 
</P>
</TEXT>
