<HEADLINE> U.S. to Re-negotiate Military Presence in Panama </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PANAMA CITY, April 6 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. Congress is planning
to re-negotiate with the new Panamanian government on establishing
a permanent presence at the U.S. military base in the country
after the year 2000, local media reported Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Miguel Bush, a legislator of the ruling Democratic
Revolutionary Party (DRP), was quoted by the press as saying the
negotiations are being encouraged because of the possibility of a
lack of cooperation after the May 2 elections by the Panamanian
government in the fight against drug trafficking.
</P>
<P>
About 80 percent of the drugs which flow into the United States
reportedly come from Columbia and go through the Panamanian
province of Colon on the Atlantic coast, which has caused concern
and encouraged the U.S. to seek re-negotiations.
</P>
<P>
The Panamanian parliament has warned that it may be necessary
to form an elite military group to halt the flow of drugs, or else
there could be a change in the local situation that could be
dangerous to Panamanian society."
</P>
<P>
According to the treaties Torrijos-Kater signed in 1977, the
United States must withdraw their troops before the year 2000 and
return the canal to Panama.
</P>
<P>
The two countries previously negotiated the formation of a "
multinational anti-drug center," (MAC) to continue the fight
against drug-trafficking after the withdrawal of the U.S. troops
from the canal.
</P>
<P>
The negotiations, which lasted almost two years, failed last
year because of differing opinions on the role of the MAC.
</P>
<P>
However, the United States has asked for an opportunity to re-
negotiate on the permanent presence of U.S. military bases in
Panama after the year 2000. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
