<HEADLINE> Chinese Doctors Rebuild Child's Cranium </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHENYANG, April 7 (Xinhua) -- Surgeons in the city of Shenyang,
the capital of northeast China's Liaoning Province, have
successfully restored the cranium of a 13-year-old who had to have
a craniotomy.
</P>
<P>
The child, Ma Hongxue, had to have brain surgery to relieve a
hemorrhage of blood vessels that were congenitally deformed.
</P>
<P>
Doctors at People's Hospital No.1 who opened Ma's skull put the
bone fragment under refrigeration for three months before they
were ready to restore it. Clinical checks during a six-month
period after the surgery showed that the fragment was mending
properly.
</P>
<P>
The hospital has successfully performed similar surgical
operations on some 20 adult patients since 1994, but this was the
first time for such an operation to be performed on a child.
</P>
</TEXT>
