<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Myanmar's Elderly Population Increases </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
YANGON, April 7 (Xinhua) -- Myanmar's elderly population,
generally in the age group of 60 and above, increased to 7.65
percent of the total population in 1997-98 fiscal year from 6.4
percent in 1990-91, according to the country's Central Health
Education Bureau.
</P>
<P>
Myanmar's population reached 46.4 million in the year,
maintaining annual growth rate of 1.87 percent.
</P>
<P>
Elderly people in Myanmar are very much respected and are
always accorded a special place of honor both within the household
and in the community at large.
</P>
<P>
Social isolation of the elderly even after widowhood is very
rare in Myanmar.
</P>
<P>
With extended family system, close social networks and local
religious institutions, the elderly in the country can play a part
in family life, community or religious activities, which create
the opportunity to improve an elderly person's self-worth and
enable older people to make valuable contribution to society.
</P>
<P>
In Myanmar, health care project activities for the elderly was
first established in 1992 and is now being implemented in 14
townships in five states and divisions.
</P>
<P>
Myanmar people recognizes and highly appreciates the efforts
made by the elderly for the family, community and national
development. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
