<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Natural Chinese Sturgeon Spawning Ground Found in Hubei </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WUHAN, April 7 (Xinhua) -- A natural spawning ground of Chinese
sturgeon on the Yangtze River has calmed fears that the damming of
the river's upper reaches could harm the breeding of the rare fish.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese sturgeon is considered a living fossil that is a
survival from the age of dinosaurs. It is on the verge of
extinction and has been given special State protection.
</P>
<P>
The rare fish spawns by swimming upstream and the damming of
the river's Gazhouba section was thought to have block the
spawning route.
</P>
<P>
Liu Yong, the head of a Chinese Sturgeon Research Center in
Hubei Province, says that the natural breeding ground was found
downstream near the dam, where the flow is gentle and temperatures
fluctuate little. A 200-km. section on the middle reaches near the
spawning spot has good conditions for breeding and many fish
species that were thought to inhabit only the upper reaches could
adapt easily adapt to life there, Liu says.
</P>
<P>
The government of the city of Yichang has increased protection
for the breeding ground and introduced a ban on fishing here and
the Hubei research center has hatched 3.9 million of the fish to
add to the river over the past decade. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990407.0254 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-07 </DATE_TIME>
