<HEADLINE> Cholera Patients Up to 223 in South Brazil State </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRAZILIA, April 6 (Xinhua) -- A major seafood market was
temporarily closed on Tuesday as one of the measures to stop the
spread of cholera in Paranagua, a city in Brazil's south Parana
state, where 223 people has been infected in the epidemic.
</P>
<P>
The Municipal Market, one of the traditional outlets of fish,
oysters and other seafood, was closed under the order of Mayor
Mario Roque.
</P>
<P>
Local students have been mobilized to spread information about
cholera to their parents, relatives and neighbors.
</P>
<P>
A medical team from Brazilian Health Ministry left for the city
on Tuesday, and will begin distributing hypochlorite salts on
Wednesday to disinfect water in the epidemic areas.
</P>
<P>
Parana's neighboring states, such as Sao Paulo, Mato Grosso do
Sul and Santa Catarina, have also declared a cholera alert.
</P>
<P>
Health agents of the neighboring states have set up checkpoints
on the border to inspect buses, cars and trucks coming from Parana.
</P>
