<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Myanmar Introduces Tax Relief Measure for Property </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
YANGON, April 7 (Xinhua) -- The Myanmar Ministry of Finance and
Revenue has introduced a fresh measure of tax relief to cope with
the increasing number of sale of properties developed by the
country's housing and municipal authorities.
</P>
<P>
Aimed at drawing more buyers for the land, buildings,
warehouses and apartments developed by the Department of Human
Settlement and Housing Development (DHSHD), the Yangon City
Development Committee and construction entrepreneurs, developers
are being advised to fix five percent more than the price for the
properties, while buyers shall not be subject to scrutiny over the
money paid for the properties.
</P>
<P>
The latest issue of the Myanmar Business News, published by the
Myanmar Chamber of Commerce and Industry, quoted a recent
notification of the ministry as saying that buyers, on their part,
are to transfer the five percent extra charge to the township
Internal Revenue Department concerned within a month after
transactions are carried out.
</P>
<P>
Previously, buyers are subject to scrutiny over the source of
their income as required by Myanmar's tax laws, having to pay due
tax for the amount for which they cannot declare the source.
</P>
<P>
The new measure introduced has affected removal of the worry of
the buyers, the Business News said.
</P>
<P>
In recent years, the Myanmar government has been implementing
schemes of housing, land-plot development and slum area upgrading
in cooperation with the private construction enterprises in order
to ensure town and city development and also to raise the living
standard of the people.
</P>
<P>
In 1997-98 fiscal year, 318,846 land plots in 16 townships,
including five newly-established ones in Yangon where industrial
zones lie, have been developed by the DHSHD, registering an
increase of 8,831 plots as compared to 310,015 plots in the
previous year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
