<HEADLINE> Army Medics Help Tibet's Civilians </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Hundreds of medical workers in army uniforms are visiting
patients in remote areas of the Tibet Autonomous Region. Forty-
five medical teams have recently been sent by the army to local
farming and animal-breeding areas.
</P>
<P>
"They are doing seasonal medical check-ups for Tibetan farmers
and herdsmen," said an army medical official.
</P>
<P>
Over the past two decades, army doctors have treated individual
Tibetans in as many as 10 million cases, and many army hospitals
have opened special wards for civilian patients.
</P>
<P>
The General Hospital of the Tibet Area Command of the People's
Liberation Army alone has taken care of local patients for some 60,
000 times and spent over one million yuan on their treatment.
</P>
<P>
Since 1978, the army hospitals have sent over 180 medical teams
to investigate, tackle and cure epidemics and diseases in remote
areas. Army medical experts have also helped train more than 10,
000 medical staff for local hospitals and clinics.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, a number of civilian hospitals have been built with
the help of the army. 
</P>
