<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Indonesian House Ratifies Anti-Discrimination Law </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, April 7 (Xinhua) -- Indonesia's House of
Representatives (DPR) has passed a bill on the ratification of the
1965 International Convention on the Elimination of All Forms of
Racial Discrimination.
</P>
<P>
In a plenary session here on Tuesday, the House of
Representatives unanimously endorsed the bill on the ratification
of the convention for President B.J. Habibie to sign into a new
law.
</P>
<P>
The ratification requires the government to, among other
things, scrap all its racial discriminatory policies, which mostly
target Chinese-Indonesian rather than descents of other migrant
groups, the Jakarta Post said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The four House factions, through their respective spokesmen,
agreed that racism must be stamped out.
</P>
<P>
While supporting the anti-racism law, the Indonesian Democratic
Party faction called on the government to revoke a 1967
presidential decree on the Religion, Beliefs and Customs of the
Chinese, because it tends to muzzle the traditions of the nation's
ethnic Chinese.
</P>
<P>
Ethnic Chinese have repeatedly complained about rampant
discriminatory practices that systematically treat them as
second-class citizens. Their identity cards bear special codes,
and careers in the military and bureaucracy are virtually closed
to them.
</P>
<P>
Spokesman for the Golkar Party faction Karsidi said human
rights are basic rights possessed by human beings, irrespective of
ethnicity or skin color, and universal in nature.
</P>
<P>
The Armed Forces spokesman Isnawan advised the government to
revoke any law that oppose the international convention as soon as
possible.
</P>
<P>
Hadimulyo of the United Development Party said the enactment of
the convention is part of Indonesia's effort to enforce and uphold
human rights which had so far been ignored.
</P>
<P>
All four factions of the House were all united in hoping that
the ratification would lay the foundation for promotion of
equality for all.
</P>
<P>
To follow up on its implementation, Minister of Justice Muladi
said a team would soon be assigned to evaluate all laws that might
be affected by the ratification.
</P>
<P>
All existing laws that went against the ratified convention
would be abolished and new ones would be made accordingly, Muladi
said in his statement welcoming the ratification. 
</P>
</TEXT>
