<HEADLINE> Lakes Drying Up In Qinghai (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
XINING, April 7 (Xinhua) -- More than 1,000 lakes in one county
of northwest China's Qinghai Province that is located at the
source of the Yellow River have dried up because of the
deteriorating environment and lack of rain.
</P>
<P>
The water level of other lakes in the area has dropped 2 to 3
meters on average, according to the county government and
ecologists are calling for immediate measures to protect the
environment at the source of the Yellow River.
</P>
<P>
Mado County covers a 25,000-sq.km. area and originally had 4,
077 lakes that were more than a sq.km., but some of the smaller
ones that used to dot the grassland and river valleys have dried
up and the water level in 2 of the largest have reportedly dropped
more than 3 m. and in the 253-sq.km. Heihai it is down 3 m. and
its shoreline has shrunk 30 m.
</P>
<P>
About 1.6 million ha. of grasslands, or 70 percent of the
county's total, has deteriorated as well, affecting the local
animal husbandry, which once gave the county's herdsmen the
highest per capita income in the country.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990407.0265 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Lakes Drying Up in Qinghai (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Qinghai's section of the Yellow River is 1,694 km. long and its
annual average outflow accounts for half the river's total. But
the river's water in the province has decreased 23 percent since
the late 1980s, according to Lu Houyu, a member of the Qinghai
Provincial Committee of the Chinese People's Political
Consultative Conference, who has just finished a study of the
environment.
</P>
<P>
The river has been drying up more frequently in certain
sections and for longer periods than when it was reported along
the lower reaches in 1972.
</P>
<P>
The provincial government has a program to plant more trees at
the sources of the Yellow and Yangtze rivers to increase the water
storage of the soil and the Central Committee of the Chinese
Communist Youth League, the State Forestry Administration, and the
China Youth Development Foundation have sponsored a "Protecting
Mother Rivers" project.
</P>
<P>
Environmentalists say that there is still a long way to go
before the ecology at the source of the rivers can be restored and
restoring the lakes that have dried up in Mado County is very
difficult, they say. 
</P>
</TEXT>
