<HEADLINE> Technology Helping Customs Officers In Guangdong </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 7 (Xinhua) -- Customs officers in the city of
Zhuhai in south China's Guangdong Province have been using high-
tech devices in their crackdown on land and sea smuggling, today's
overseas edition of the People's Daily reports.
</P>
<P>
The high-tech system has so far helped thwart more than 330
cases of smuggling by ship, valued at more than 177 million yuan (
21 million US dollars).
</P>
<P>
Customs officers in the city's Gongbei district first developed
a computerized anti-smuggling system using telecommunications
equipment, radar-tracking, and other electronic devices to improve
the means of telecommunications and shorten the amount of time
needed to confirm suspected targets.
</P>
<P>
To uncover smugglers from among the endless line of motor
vehicles and containers crossing the border at Gongbei, Customs
officers use large electronic scales. One customs officer found a
cardboard box that was especially heavy and discovered 75,000
pirated discs inside when he examined it.
</P>
<P>
Customs officers have also developed a mathematical model for
picking out smugglers from the line of people passing through with
the analytical help of the computerized system. It also means that
ordinary passengers can avoid unnecessary checks.
</P>
<P>
The system helped customs officers discover more than 150 cases
of smuggling in the past year while reducing the number of
officers needed from 57 to 21.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990407.0273 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-07 </DATE_TIME>
