<HEADLINE> Indonesia's Foreign Direct Investment Drops Sharply </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, April 7 (Xinhua) -- Foreign direct investment approved
by the Indonesian government in the first quarter of this year
plunged almost 90 percent to 560 million U.S. dollars from 5.1
billion dollars during the same period last year, a senior
official said.
</P>
<P>
Licensed foreign investment projects fell to 187 from 304 from
January to March 15, Antara News Agency Wednesday quoted State
Minister of Investment Hamzah Haz as saying.
</P>
<P>
In the meantime, only 36 domestic investment projects had been
approved during the said period of 1999, a decline of 64.4 percent
compared to 91 projects in 1998, said the minister Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
However, in terms of value, Hamzah said, the domestic
investment projects increased by 217 percent to 53.7 billion
rupiah (6.1 billion U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
"But, not all the approved projects have been realized by their
investors," he added.
</P>
<P>
According to the latest report from the investors, the
realization of their projects have been very slow, reaching only
35 percent as the result of lack of money, decline in natural
resources, low worker skills, lack of technology, and marketing
problems.
</P>
<P>
"However, although the realization of foreign and domestic
investment had been low, their contribution to the growth of
non-oil and gas exports has been quite significant," he said.
</P>
<P>
The minister said that in the current prolonged economic
crisis, many companies have stopped operating, while others went
on realizing their projects. 
</P>
</TEXT>
