<HEADLINE> City Sculptures Carve out Place </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 7 (Xinhua) -- Excited is the right word to
describe Wang Jinghui and Chen Shengzheng in the light of their
animated discussions on the national urban sculpture designs
exhibition "Hope of the New Century", China Daily reported today.
</P>
<P>
"I didn't expect to see so many ingenious designs," said Chen,
a professor at the Lu Xun Academy of Fine Arts.
</P>
<P>
He was one of the main forces in the creation of the group of
sculptures in front of Beijing Agricultural Exhibition Hall. These
sculptures won the Best Design Prize in China's first urban
sculpture design contest in 1987, the newspaper said.
</P>
<P>
Wang, chief planner at the China Urban Planning and Design
Institute, said he was "inspired" to find China's urban sculpture
designs had progressed so well over the past 50 years.
</P>
<P>
"The exhibition contains the very latest gems of urban
sculptures from all over the world," he said.
</P>
<P>
The five-day exhibition, which closed yesterday in Beijing,
boasted more than 120 models of urban sculptures, large sculptures
intended to be placed outdoors. The selection was whittled down
from over 700 submissions, the newspaper said.
</P>
<P>
In terms of the development of urban sculpture in China, Chen
divided this century into two halves - the country's once-splendid
art of urban sculpture was on the decline before 1949, while it
has been on the upswing since then.  
</P>
