<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Backgrounder: ABCs of Macao SAR Basic Law (16) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 7 (Xinhua) -- Following is Part 16 of a question
and answer series of the ABCs of the Basic Law of the Macao
Special Administrative Region (SAR).
</P>
<P>
Why can the MSAR use its own regional flag and regional emblem?
</P>
<P>
Display and use of the regional flag and regional emblem by
MSAR is provided in Article 10 of the Basic Law.
</P>
<P>
This article highlights the high degree of autonomy enjoyed by
the MSAR and facilitates its conduct of external exchanges.
</P>
<P>
According to Article 13 and Chapter 7 of the Basic Law, the
MSAR may, with the authorization of the Central People's
Government, conduct its own extensive external affairs in
accordance with the Basic Law.
</P>
<P>
For instance, the MSAR may, on its own, using the name "Macao,
China", maintain and develop relations and conclude and implement
agreements with foreign states and regions and relevant
international organizations in appropriate fields, including those
in the economic, trade, financial, monetary, shipping,
communications, tourism, culture, science and technology, and
sport sectors.
</P>
<P>
Using the name " Macao, China", it may participate in
international organizations and conferences not limited to states.
It may set up official or semi-official economic and trade offices
in foreign countries.
</P>
<P>
Without its regional flag and regional emblem, the MSAR will be
inconvenienced in conducting the above external activities.
</P>
<P>
The regional flag of the MSAR is a green flag with five stars,
lotus flower, bridge and sea-water. The five stars symbolize
national unification and the fact that Macao is an inalienable
part of the People's Republic of China.
</P>
<P>
Lotus flower is a popular local flower in Macao. In the old
days, Macao was also known as the "land of the lotus" and "lotus
stem." Its three petals represent the Macao Peninsula, Taipa
Island and Coloane Island. The whole lotus flower symbolizes the
prosperity of the future Macao. The bridge and sea water below the
lotus flower reflect the natural conditions of Macao, and the
green flag symbolizes the thriving land of China including Macao.
</P>
<P>
The regional emblem of the MSAR is composed of five stars,
lotus, bridge and sea water encircled by the words "Macao Special
Administrative Region of the People's Republic of China" in
Chinese and "MACAO" in Portuguese. This shows that both Chinese
and Portuguese are official languages in Macao.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990407.0277 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Backgrounder: ABCs of Macao SAR Basic Law (15) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 7 (Xinhua) -- Following is Part 15 of a question
and answer series of the ABCs of the Basic Law of the Macao
Special Administrative Region (SAR).
</P>
<P>
What kinds of laws are now in force in Macao?
</P>
<P>
There are two kinds of laws currently in force in Macao.
</P>
<P>
The first are Portuguese laws, including those enacted in
Portugal whose legal force extends to Macao and Portuguese laws
enacted specially for Macao.
</P>
<P>
The second kind is local, which are mainly laws, decrees,
administrative regulations and other acts introduced by the local
legislature and other competent organs in Macao.
</P>
<P>
The laws, decrees, administrative regulations and other acts
previously in force in Macao referred to in Article 8 of the Basic
Law cover only the local laws in Macao which are still in force on
December 19, 1999.
</P>
<P>
The Portuguese laws enacted by competent Portuguese bodies,
whether those which are extended to cover Macao or those enacted
specifically for Macao, will no longer be deemed as the laws
previously in force in Macao with the resumption of exercise of
sovereignty over Macao by the Chinese Government as from the date
of the establishment of the MSAR.
</P>
<P>
These Portuguese laws shall not be maintained unless they have
been converted into local laws in Macao through proper
localization procedures before the above date.
</P>
<P>
However, in the case of citing the Portuguese laws by the local
Macao laws, a flexible approach may be adopted, as has been done
in the case of Hong Kong. The principle to be observed in this
regard is that such citation must not infringe upon China's
sovereignty and does not contravene the Basic Law.
</P>
<P>
It should be pointed out that the maintenance of the laws
previously in force in Macao is not unconditional. According to
Article 8 of the Basic Law, for the laws previously in force in
Macao to be maintained, they shall not contravene the Basic Law.
</P>
<P>
For instance, laws which are colonial in nature and infringe
upon China's sovereignty and which are clearly inconsistent with
the Basic Law in terms of the relationship between the central
government and the MSAR shall not be maintained.
</P>
<P>
These laws are subject to amendment by the legislature or other
relevant bodies of the MSAR in accordance with legal procedures.
</P>
<P>
With Macao's return to China, the legislature or other relevant
organs of the MSAR are bound to make due amendments to some
obsolete laws previously in force in Macao. Such obsolete laws
shall not be maintained.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990407.0278 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Archaeological Discoveries in North China Province </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TAIYUAN, April 7 (Xinhua) -- Chinese archaeologists have
discovered a large number of ancient tombs and bronze articles,
dating back to the Spring and Autumn period (770-476 B.C.) and the
Warring States period (475-221 B.C.), in Houma City in Shanxi
Province.
</P>
<P>
The discovery will provide valuable clues for archaeological
research into the Jin State, an ancient kingdom of the Spring and
Autumn periods with Houma as its capital.
</P>
<P>
So far, more than 300 tombs and 500 pits used in ancient
ceremonies have been unearthed in a construction area of the city
since early last year. Over 500 historical relics including bronze,
pottery and jade articles have been excavated from the tombs.
</P>
<P>
Among the relics, the most rare is a pressurized bronze cooking
vessel that even contains some food from the ancient time.
</P>
<P>
Archaeological prospecting technology proves that there are a
total of 3,000 ancient tombs and 1,000 pits still buried in the
area. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
