<HEADLINE> FIFA President Reassures Africa on 2006 World Cup </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, April 6 (Xinhua) -- President of the Federation of
International Football Association (FIFA) Sepp Blatter Tuesday
reassured that Africa should host the 2006 World Cup.
</P>
<P>
Addressing a press conference here, he noted that in 1994, U.S.
hosted the World Cup, in 1998 Europe had it while the 2002 World
Cup would be hosted in Asia, adding no doubt it is the turn of
Africa in the year of 2006.
</P>
<P>
Africa has contributed to the development of football in the
world, he noted, his conviction that an African nation would host
the 2006 World Cup had not changed.
</P>
<P>
So far, eight countries including such African countries as
South Africa, Egypt, Morocco, Ghana and Nigeria have all bid for
the 2006 World Cup.
</P>
<P>
On the organizing effort made by Nigerians, the FIFA president
said the preparations made by the Local Organizing Committee (LOC)
concerning the facilities of stadia, training grounds, hotels and
transport are very good.
</P>
<P>
FIFA is "satisfied and very happy with the organizational
efforts Nigeria has undertaken all around the country," Blatter
pointed out.
</P>
<P>
He noted that the general assessment of the tournament was
better than what was reported and printed by the press, saying he
was impressed by the facilities put in place.
</P>
<P>
"The stadium, training pitches, hotels, the teams and everybody
have make me happy," Blatter said.
</P>
<P>
Asked about the blackout at the on-going 10th World Youth
Championship tagged Nigeria '99, the FIFA president said that he
understood power outage as a common problem in Africa, and power
blackout happens even in Australia and European countries.
</P>
<P>
After the embarrassment caused by a blackout in Ibadan during
Mexico's game with Ireland, President Blatter suffered a similar
incident in Kano when he held a press briefing.
</P>
<P>
He disclosed that FIFA was considering a propsal to hold the
Women's World Cup every two years as a way of promoting women
football all over the world.
</P>
<P>
After attending the opening ceremony on April 3 in Lagos,
Blatter went to watch first match of the Ibadan zone's game and
then that in Kano.
</P>
<P>
The FIFA president is scheduled to leave for Zurich Tuesday
evening and to return to the West African country for the
semifinals and final matches of Nigeria '99. 
</P>
</TEXT>
