<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mummies Dating 5 Centuries Ago Found in Argentina </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BUENOS AIRES, April 6 (Xinhua) -- A group of archeologists have
discovered three well-preserved Inca mummies high in the Andes
Mountains inside Argentina.
</P>
<P>
The three, relics of an Inca sacrificial ritual more than 500
years ago, were found beneath 1.5 meters of rock and earth on a
burial platform atop Argentina's Mount Llullaillaco about 6,739-
meter high above the sea level, according to a communique of the
Argentine Culture and Education Ministry.
</P>
<P>
The bodies of two girls and a boy may have been frozen since
being placed there, officials said.
</P>
<P>
Archeologist Johan Reinhard said in a statement that CT scans
on the mummies showed all internal organs intact and blood
appeared to still be present in the heart and lungs, as if the
three had died only recently.
</P>
<P>
No cause of death was immediately evident, he said.
</P>
<P>
The expedition was formed by Argentine, Peruvian and U.S.
archeologists. The started their work a month ago.
</P>
<P>
The researchers said the burial platform held offerings to the
Inca gods, including 36 gold, silver and shell statues, ornate
textiles, moccasins and pottery.
</P>
<P>
The Inca empire once stretched 4,000 kilometers from the
present day Colombia to central Chile. It collapsed in 1532 with
the Spanish conquest.
</P>
<P>
Argentina's Salta Province has announced the discovery as a
cultural heritage. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
