<HEADLINE> Xinhua World News Summary at 0100 GMT, April 7 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA -- China and Turkey on Tuesday agreed to further develop
bilateral ties in all fields.
</P>
<P>
The agreement was reached during talks between Turkish
President Suleyman Demirel and visiting Chairman of the Standing
Committee of the National People's Congress of China Li Peng.
</P>
<P>
Demirel said that Turkey attaches great importance to
developing friendly ties with China, which is playing an important
role in the world. (Turkey-China-Li Peng)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS -- The U.N. Security Council Tuesday continued
the discussion on whether or not to have a draft resolution or
some other form of response to reflect the latest developments
concerning Libya.
</P>
<P>
U.N. spokesman Fred Eckhard told a press conference that the
latest developments include the Libyan handover of two Lockerbie
suspects for a trial before a Scottish court in the Netherlands, a
U.N. spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
Such developments also include the suspension of the sanctions
against Libya, he said.
</P>
<P>
The chairman of the committee which monitors the sanctions
against Libya is expected to issue a note verbale to States and
organizations restating that the sanctions have been suspended,
Eckhard said. (UN-Lockerbie-Statement)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
CAIRO -- Egypt has decided to send relief to Kosovo ethnic
Albanian refugees, sources of the Egyptian Red Crescent Society
said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The sources said the humanitarian aid will be flown Wednesday
to the refugees, who have been pouring into neighboring Albania
and Macedonia since the North Atlantic Treaty Organization (NATO)
began its air-strikes against Serb targets on March 24.
</P>
<P>
The sources said the relief goods include 5.4 tons of medicines,
1,500 boxes of milk powder, 500 boxes of canned foodstuffs and 1,
000 blankets, the Middle East News Agency reported. (Egypt-Kosovo-
Aid)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
BRUSSELS -- The North Atlantic Treaty Organization (NATO)
Tuesday formally refused to accept Yugoslavia's peace proposal as
the NATO chief said the cease-fire offer "is clearly insufficient.
"
</P>
<P>
NATO Secretary-General Javier Solana said in a statement that
the unilateral cease-fire proposed by the Yugoslav and Serbian
governments did not meet NATO's demand. "Before a cease-fire can
be considered, President Milosevic must meet the demands
established by the international community," he said. (NATO-
Yugoslavia-Peace Proposal)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
WASHINGTON -- Secretary of State Madeleine Albright Tuesday
outlined NATO's new mission two weeks before its 50th anniversary,
saying the Kosovo operation presages the new non-territorial
missions the alliance will conduct next century.
</P>
<P>
In a speech to the Brookings Institution, a Washington-based
think tank, Albright said NATO will retain its core mission in the
21st century, but it must also undertake out-of-area missions like
those in Bosnia and Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
U.S. officials said NATO leaders are ready to approve the
concept of non-territorial missions at their Washington summit,
which will be held in two weeks when leaders of 19 NATO countries
meet to chart their future course.
</P>
<P>
But the allies have still not agreed on how that concept will
reflect the connection between NATO and the United Nations.
</P>
<P>
There is broad agreement NATO should obtain a U.N. mandate
before undertaking a mission outside its traditional area and
there must be flexibility for those instances when obtaining that
mandate is not possible, the officials said.
</P>
<P>
With regard to Kosovo, she called NATO's airstrikes against
Yugoslavia a test for the Western alliance "before the new century
even begins," and asserted that Washington would be "prepared for
an extended conflict." (US-NATO-Albright)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
WASHINGTON, April 6 (Xinhua) -- Vice President Al Gore Tuesday
asked Russian Prime Minister Yevgeny Primakov to use his influence
to urge Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic to accept NATO's
demands on how to end the NATO bombing campaign.
</P>
<P>
A Gore aide said the two leaders talked for about 40 minutes
through telephone and their conversation was "candid and
businesslike."
</P>
<P>
Gore and Primakov agreed to stay in contact. It was not clear
when Gore would be meeting Primakov as part of their joint U.S.-
Russian commission to work on long-term problems. Primakov was
coming to Washington for a meeting of the commission when he
turned back in protest at NATO's bombing campaign. (US-Kosovo-Gore-
Primakov) 
</P>
