<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Hails WTO Ruling on Banana Dispute </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, April 6 (Xinhua) -- The United States on Tuesday
hailed a ruling by the World Trade Organization (WTO) which
cleared the way for the U.S. government to impose 100 percent
tariffs on nearly 200 million U.S. dollars worth of imports from
the European Union (EU) in retaliation to EU's banana import
regime.
</P>
<P>
"We are pleased that the WTO arbitrators concur with our
position that the EU banana regime is WTO-inconsistent and
continues to damage the U.S. economy," U.S. Trade Representative
Charlene Barshefsky said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
However, the amount subject to punitive tariffs under the WTO
ruling was significantly less than the 520 million dollars
originally sought by the United States. The tariffs would be
effective retroactively to March 3.
</P>
<P>
The dispute, which pitted major U.S. fruit distributors against
their European rivals, contributed to a deterioration in U.S.-
European trade relations, which were also strained by an argument
over beef treated with growth hormones.
</P>
<P>
The United States put importers on notice last month that they
may be liable to pay punitive duties on some EU products should
the WTO rule in Washington's favor. The decision to effectively
impose duties ahead of the WTO arbitration panel's decision caused
an uproar in EU countries.
</P>
<P>
In a briefing, U.S. special trade negotiator Peter Scher called
the decision a "major victory" and said it could set an important
precedent for disputes with Europe over hormone treated beef and
with Canada over magazines. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990407.0302 </DOCNO>
