<HEADLINE> Hundreds of PNG People Fled, Fearing Quake-related </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, April 7 (Xinhua) -- Hundreds of people in the
northern coastal town of Lae in Papua New Guinea's (PNG) Morobe
province have fled their homes on the beach after two strong
earthquakes hit the area and raised fears of a tsunami.
</P>
<P>
There has been no reports of injuries or damage, the Australian
Associated Press (AAP) said in a report released earlier
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The wire service quoted local police as reporting people
panicked when an earthquake was felt about 7.30pm Tuesday night
and another smaller one followed around 9.30 p.m.
</P>
<P>
A rumor spread that Lae would be hit by a tsunami similar to
the one that devastated an area of PNG's north-west coast near
Aitape in July last year, killing thousands of people.
</P>
<P>
"Somebody went around and started telling everybody that we're
expecting something similar to Aitape," the duty officer at the
Lae police station, Sergeant Major Pauline Siaguru, told AAP.
</P>
<P>
Frightened residents left their homes in the settlements along
the beach and moved inland.
</P>
<P>
Siaguru said police had managed to convince most people to
return home after telling them that there would not be a tsunami.
</P>
<P>
"The situation is back to normal now," Siaguru said.
</P>
<P>
Siaguru said the first earthquake was strong enough to shake
items "off the shelf" at the police station.
</P>
<P>
No details are available yet on the size of the earthquakes.
</P>
<P>
PNG has experienced several earthquakes in the last two days.
</P>
<P>
On Monday night an earthquake measuring 7.4 on the Richter
scale shook the island of New Britain, 250 km north of the
capital, Port Moresby.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
