<HEADLINE> Finland to Offer More Aid to Kosovar Refugees </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HELSINKI, April 6 (Xinhua) -- Finland's Diplomatic and Security
Policies Commission Tuesday convened an emergency meeting on the
Kosovo situation and decided to increase aid to the Kosovar
refugees.
</P>
<P>
A statement issued by the government said that recent days saw
the refugee situation worsen. Some neighboring countries were no
longer able to stand the growing human tide.
</P>
<P>
The statement said that Finland was prepared to further
increase aid to the refugees on the basis of the earlier provision
of eight million Finnish marks (1.37 million U.S. dollars). The
government is also working on the dispatch of medical teams from
the Finnish Red Cross organizations to the main refugee areas, the
statement added.
</P>
<P>
Finland was also ready to accept a small number of about 50
refugees in extremely poor health, according to Prime Minister
Paavo Lipponen.
</P>
<P>
As the flood of refugees has increased, Finnish citizens have
been generous in their donations. So far, the Red Cross has
collected up to one million Finnish marks (171,100 dollars).
</P>
<P>
The Red Cross and some other relief agencies have transported a
variety of relief goods including tents, clothing, medicine and
sanitary goods to the disaster areas. 
</P>
