<HEADLINE> Tibet Cracks down on Relics-Related Crimes </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LHASA, April 7 (Xinhua) -- The Tibet Autonomous Region has
launched a large-scale crack down on relics-related crimes and
international relics smugglers.
</P>
<P>
The regional government has urged police to solve a number of
major relices-related cases as soon as possible, together with
customs offices, judicial departments and religious affairs
departments.
</P>
<P>
According to official figures, since 1994, 120 relics-related
cases took place in Tibet, with 541 pieces of ancient Tibetan
relics lost. So far, 70 of the cases have been solved and 314
pieces of the relics returned.
</P>
<P>
In recent years, criminal activities like theft, robbery,
smuggling and trafficking of ancient relics have been on the rise
in this southwest China autonomous region.
</P>
<P>
Nowadays in the Tibet Autonomous Region, tourists are visiting
local lamaseries and other ancient places much more frequently
than any others.
</P>
<P>
However, equipped with mini-cameras, these special "pilgrims"
stealthily take pictures of the valuables and then publish
shopping directories, in the forms of books and discs distributed
through underground channels, or via the Internet.
</P>
<P>
Some local officials in charge of the matter attribute the
growth in relics-related crimes to the increasingly rising prices
of Tibetan relics on the international market.
</P>
<P>
Money has driven local traffickers, some of whom are connected
with foreign smugglers, to try every means to steal valuable
Tibetan relics.
</P>
<P>
The rising relics-related criminal activities have drawn
concern from local authorities. The regional government has
decided to punish relics-related criminals severely according to
law.
</P>
<P>
The local police and customs departments held a special
exhibition in an effort to create public awareness among local
people about the importance of protecting Tibetan relics and to
combat criminals. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
