<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Gore Calls Primakov on Kosovo Bombing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, April 6 (Xinhua) -- Vice President Al Gore Tuesday
asked Russian Prime Minister Yevgeny Primakov to use his influence
to urge Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic to accept NATO's
demands on how to end the NATO bombing campaign.
</P>
<P>
A Gore aide said the two leaders talked for about 40 minutes
through telephone and their conversation was "candid and
businesslike."
</P>
<P>
NATO's demands are that Milosevic withdraw Serb forces from
their sovereign territory of Kosovo Province, which has already
been rejected by Belgrade.
</P>
<P>
Primakov went to Belgrade in the opening days of the war to
meet Milosevic, who agreed to a partial withdrawal of Serb forces
from Kosovo on the condition that NATO stop bombing. But the
allies rejected the plan.
</P>
<P>
David Leavy, spokesman for the White House National Security
Council, said that if Milosevic agreed to NATO demands, then a
scenario could be envisioned where "other non-NATO countries could
participate" in the so-called peacekeeping force.
</P>
<P>
Gore and Primakov agreed to stay in contact. It was not clear
when Gore would be meeting Primakov as part of their joint
U.S.-Russian commission to work on long-term problems. Primakov
was coming to Washington for a meeting of the commission when he
turned back in protest at NATO's bombing campaign. 
</P>
</TEXT>
