<BODY>
<HEADLINE> FIFA President Stands for Biennial World Cup </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, April 6 (Xinhua) -- President of Federation of
International Football Association (FIFA) Sepp Blatter Tuesday
said that a biennial World Cup would offer a lot of opportunities
to many football federations to host soccer's most-prestigious
competition.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a crowded press conference here, the FIFA president
who arrived in Nigeria on April 2 said that he had definitely not
changed his mind about the idea which, he said, was good for the
game.
</P>
<P>
"The biennial World Cup will mean more contacts in
international football competitions, more possibilities for
countries in Africa and Asia to host the game," he noted.
</P>
<P>
Blatter who is in Nigeria for the on-going 10th World Youth
Championship tagged Nigeria '99 from April 3 to 24 pointed out "it
will be possible for the hosting of the World Cup to turn around
the global more often."
</P>
<P>
Under the present arrangement of four-yearly staging of the
competition, he added, it would take 24 years to get back to the
same continent, using the six continents of the world.
</P>
<P>
He noted that the present critics of a biennial World Cup were
mainly the clubs in Europe who were always reluctant to release
players for their national teams.
</P>
<P>
The FIFA president observed that an arrangement could be worked
out to have a unified international football calender, which would
have specific periods to play and a certain period set aside for
national teams.
</P>
<P>
"I am still for the two yearly World Cup because it would be
good for the game, especially in this jet age," he stressed.
</P>
<P>
Blatter is scheduled to leave Tuesday night the West african
country for the FIFA headquarters in Zurich and will return to
Nigeria when the current game enters the semifinal and final
stages. 
</P>
</TEXT>
