<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese, British Actuarial Cooperation Fruitful </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 7 (Xinhua) -- Another seven Chinese graduate
students have become internationally recognized actuaries.
</P>
<P>
They were awarded the qualification certificate by the master's
program co-sponsored by the British Institute of Actuaries, Eagle
Star Insurance Company and China's Central University of Finance
and Economics.
</P>
<P>
The program, launched in 1993, is the first in China to train
international licensed actuaries. So far, 36 students have gained
the actuarial qualification certificate, and eight have received
their financial and investment certificate.
</P>
<P>
Developing the actuarial system and training actuaries are seen
as the key to a mature insurance sector in China, especially as
the country's Insurance Law acknowledges the role of actuaries.
It stipulates insurers operating in China should hire at least one
actuary recognized by the government's financial administration,
and have an actuarial reporting system.
</P>
<P>
Actuaries are versatile, with a knowledge of mathematics,
statistics, economics, investment and insurance. The UK's
government actuary Chris Daykin said the students in the China-
British program have made "remarkable" achievements, and their
passing rate is far higher than the international average.
</P>
<P>
China is expected to need at least 5,000 actuaries in the
coming decade. Some overseas insurance companies and international
institutions are co-sponsoring with Chinese universities related
programs and have set up examination centers.
</P>
<P>
A joint program between Fudan University and the American
International Group Inc. produced China's first actuary that is
recognized by the China Insurance Regulatory Commission, the
insurance industry watchdog.
</P>
<P>
Eagle Star is the first European insurance company to have a
presence in China. It set up a Beijing representative office in
1992, and has two more in Shanghai and Guangzhou. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990407.0319 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Albright Outlines NATO's New Mission Next Century </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, April 6 (Xinhua) -- Secretary of State Madeleine
Albright Tuesday outlined NATO's new mission two weeks before its
50th anniversary, saying the Kosovo operation presages the new
non-territorial missions the alliance will conduct next century.
</P>
<P>
In a speech to the Brookings Institution, a Washington-based
think tank, Albright said NATO will retain its core mission in the
21st century, but it must also undertake out-of-area missions like
those in Bosnia and Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
"Hopefully, they will be rare but -- as is now the case --
there may be more than one ongoing at any given time. They may be
conducted jointly with partners or other non-allied nations. And
by definition, they will involve operations outside alliance
territory, with all the logistical complications that entail," she
said.
</P>
<P>
U.S. officials said NATO leaders are ready to approve the
concept of non-territorial missions at their Washington summit,
which will be held in two weeks when leaders of 19 NATO countries
meet to chart their future course.
</P>
<P>
But the allies have still not agreed on how that concept will
reflect the connection between NATO and the United Nations.
</P>
<P>
There is broad agreement NATO should obtain a U.N. mandate
before undertaking a mission outside its traditional area and
there must be flexibility for those instances when obtaining that
mandate is not possible, the officials said.
</P>
<P>
With regard to Kosovo, Albright said: "Our explicit goal should
be to transform the Balkans from the continent's primary source of
instability into an important part of the European mainstream."
</P>
<P>
And she called NATO's airstrikes against Yugoslavia a test for
the Western alliance "before the new century even begins."
</P>
<P>
Albright spoke before Belgrade announced a unilateral
cease-fire in Kosovo, which however was rejected by the United
States and its allies. And Albright asserted that Washington would
be "prepared for an extended conflict." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990407.0320 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Arsenal Beats Blackburn </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, April 6 (Xinhua)-- Arsenal kept their premier league
title hopes alive when they defeated Blackburn Rovers to move
within one point of Manchester United in the English Premier
League on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Dennis Bergkamp scored the goal that mattered in the 42nd
minute with a rebound off his own free kick, and though he missed
a second half penalty, the reigning champions had all they needed
to keep the pressure on United even though they have played one
game more.
</P>
<P>
United are on 64 points with Arsenal on 63, four clear of third
placed Chelsea.
</P>
<P>
Blackburn defended resolutely for most of the first half until
they conceded the vital free kick. Bergkamp's effort was poor and
struck the wall at knee-level, but the rebound came back to him
and he made no mistake with a left-foot shot that beat John Filan
into the far corner.
</P>
<P>
In the 83rd minute after he was pulled down in the box by Keith
Gillespie, Bergkamp had a chance to make it 2-0 but Filan dived
low to his left to make the save.
</P>
<P>
The defeat left Blackburn mired in the relegation zone, one
position above the third-from-bottom club only on goal difference.
</P>
<P>
Two players got march orders in the match with Martin Keown in
the 69th minute for a second bookable offence and Gillespie for
his foul on Bergkamp that led to the missed penalty.
</P>
<P>
In the other premier league game, Leicester scored twice in the
last 30 minutes to salvage a 2-2 draw with former leaders Aston
Villa, who have now gone 11 games without a victory.
</P>
<P>
Villa looked likely to come out of their slump when they took a
2-0 lead early in the second half.
</P>
<P>
Lee Hendrie had given them an 80-second lead and Julian Joachim
made it 2-0 right after the break.
</P>
<P>
But Leicester delighted their home fans with a spirited
recovery which was rewarded when Robbie Savage in the 62nd minute
and Tony Cottee in the 71st struck to salvage a point. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
